 * Create separate target method

commit_message:
Remove usage of expandtabs() in get_workflow_definition

There's no need to use that function for the purpose of calculating
indentation.

This patch is supplementary to the previouse patch[1], which I have
wrongly pressed workflow+1 button to have it merged. Please see my
comments there.

Fix the wrong indentation of workflow definition as well.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225559/

Change-Id: I8daac2f81989cff83abcb01096bdf84eae5d89eb

Puppet modules are based on already released versions of midonet. It's responsibility of the puppet modules maintainers to keep the backwards compatibility with previous versions in deployment time. Moreover, puppet modules are released after the official version of OpenStack and even after their packages are available on upstream distros.

Please go on with this patch. We are aware and we have plenty of time to adapt the puppet neutron for Liberty deployment (It is not too much work at all).

I only ask you to inform us if you think a change on the source code  can imply a change on the install/configuration by opening a bug or ping us."}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-10-01 08:56:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Workflow

I had some issues with creating a unit test (no javascript on devstack etc), and since we are close to rc-2, I suggest we just push the fix as is.

If someone like to try and create a unit test, this is how I tested the fix manually:
(mistral) workflow-get-definition test_js_json
---
version: '2.0'

test_js_json:
  output:
    result: <% $.javascript_task %>

  tasks:
    javascript_task:
      action: std.javascript
      input:
        context: <% $ %>
        script: |
          return { "key": "value" };
(mistral) 
(mistral) 
(mistral) execution-create test_js_json

+-------------+--------------------------------------+
(mistral)

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).
The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

Change-Id: I5ac8602b47a747e77dc8afd579d4e280b3ed894f
Partial-Bug: #1259292

[{'created': '2015-09-18 22:42:02.000000000', 'message': "Fail task on publish error

If there's YAQL expression evaluation error in published variables for
any task, the on_action_complete fails, DB transactions rollback, and
the task is stuck in a RUNNING state. This patch sets the task state
to ERROR and save the error message in the task state_info.

Change-Id: I9003157f57f4e649610428b046c237f8f51038fb
Closes-Bug: #1496685
"}]
commit_message:
Fail task on publish error

If there's YAQL expression evaluation error in published variables for
any task, the on_action_complete fails, DB transactions rollback, and
the task is stuck in a RUNNING state. This patch sets the task state
to ERROR and save the error message in the task state_info.

Change-Id: I9003157f57f4e649610428b046c237f8f51038fb
Closes-Bug: #1496685

of result is 'plain/text'.

commit_message:
Customized response sent in case of fault condition.

When duplicate workbook or workflow is created,
html respose is sent because content type
of result is 'plain/text'.

Code has been change to send 'application/json'
content type in case of exception is araise.

Change-Id: Icef1f8c5c615e21bb9da5a3d3bef9dacd308d242
Closes-Bug: #1501172

commit_message:
[install] Liberty updates for cinder

Update cinder configuration for Liberty. Includes moving
basic host configuration of the block storage node to
environment section. Also addresses some consistency
issues, mostly from the RST conversion.

Changes and testing specific to distribution packages
primarily involve Ubuntu. Other distributions may require
additional patches.

Change-Id: I8915bc5fad5d278fd73899476bf6d90970d18564
Implements: bp installguide-liberty

commit_message:
Remove obsolete backport for oslo.log

The patch was merged upstream. Remove it from kolla tree since it
doesn't apply cleanly anymore and break openstack-base image building.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: Ia82aa10860d24d696a172ec6596076c9b6b2d0a5
Closes-Bug: #1505456
(cherry picked from commit e9ed7ca403e55fb231ece5c56d7f44a49234ad48)

I wonder if we should specify the TYPE of attribute values as a conventional practice.

for example if 'package_type' is always a list (as it seems to be applied here) that may make it easier to parse than if it's either a string or a list of strings.

I'd like this but not so much I'd -1 over it, but I would like to see the idea discussed before we push our first tags."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:28:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2015-06-01 09:24:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-01 09:47:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-06-01 23:37:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

It'd be really nice if we could add to this blueprint the fact that, for bugs, we should allow a reasonable delay to get them fixed (for example: 1 or 2 weeks), and not just a delay after the release. I can foresee the case where someone with evil intention would submit a RC bug against a package, then the same day try to remove the "quality:good" tag.

Also, in your example, there's only:

"pkgtype": ["apt"]

Packages in Debian and Ubuntu aren't currently the same. Even though there's the intention to merge during the liberty cycle, we don't know if this will happen or not. So please make the distinction.

And, on the same topic, here, I can see:

"Key management (Barbican)":
     {
        "status": "no",
        "pkgtype": ["apt"]
     }

Well, the package has just been accepted into Debian Sid (but isn't currently in Ubuntu). So that's a very good example showing the problem. :)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-02 02:15:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thomas, many thanks for looking at this.

What this tag is about is providing real information to operators. Therefore, I would not expect to insert any 'delay' to make the tag level appear better.

If there is a major packaging bug that has been discovered, the tag should be updated. It would not be acceptable to have the tag say "good" for 2 weeks when in reality the packages were unusable.



Regarding the packaging system breakdown, I'd like to see some feedback from others.

My impression is that thanks to your efforts debian is well ahead of many distros in terms of packaging. However, this needs to be carefully managed. I think this tag is best as a general state per project, and making it an exhaustive catalogue of which projects are packaged in which versions of which distros is not something that is maintainable.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-02 14:55:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Based on Jaypipe's suggestion for simplicity, I think we should even consider removing the pkgtype attribute altogether."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:28:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

(Reposting my comment from the other review here, since it's the same concern):

I think it would be simpler (and easier to navigate) if tags were just binary, rather than have multiple attributes.

Here I'm thinking of the websites that will be built soon to expose that information to the public. For TC tags we've restricted ourselves to purely binary tags (it's there or it's not) so that the information is simple to present, and does not substitute to proper documentation.

So I see 3 ways out of this maze:

1/ Turn ops tags into purely binary beings

For this tag I would just define "ops:well-packaged" like we discussed in YVR. 

2/ Publish a companion doc to expand on the tag

The tag is still binary, but has wiki/documentation associated to it to provide extra information. For this tag, that would mean moving the nuances between "beginning", "warning" and "no", as well as the list of packaged distros, to an associated document that further explains the status.

3/ Really provide ops metrics but then don't call them tags

If you think you can't provide (or are not interested in providing) binary labels, then so be it, but don't call them "tags". Reduce confusion by not using the same word for different things.

I tend to prefer 1 or 2 because that allows us to still publish them on the project tag navigation website.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:34:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks ttx!

So, #1 just doesn't work at all with the whole underlying idea of providing information to ops as our goal.

#2 I think complicates both the process of updating the tag and also using the information for display. Based on your comments, I don't think we have a common view on how this information should be displayed.

I guess this leaves #3, but I don't understand what "metrics" are in this context :)'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:37:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I guess there is also:

4/ Tag is binary but has extra attributes

Something like "ops:packaged" having a "quality" attribute that could have "beginning", "warning", "good" as values. In this precise example I think the main piece of infirmation to communicate is whether it's well-packaged, no whether it has some amount of packaging, so I'm not sure that would work that well.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:37:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:38:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

See the comment - it's not just well-packaged we care about. It's also about digging into stuff that isn't well packaged and keeping track of that."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:42:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Tom: I don't think #1 is orthogonal to providing information to ops. A binary tag can still convey precise status. But I see your point.

When I say metrics, I mean: in this proposal you're basically defining a category ("packaging") and then give a score to it (good, beginning, warning, no). It's different from a label/tag, where you define a name ("well-packaged") and rules to apply to get that label. I think calling both concepts "tag" is confusing, so if #3 is the way forward, i would call that category/concept/set-of-scores something else.

I still think you can achieve your goals with #4 though. Define a tag that is applied in a binary manner, and convey extra information through extra attributes of the tag.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

For instance, take this as an example of a "major bug":

https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/openstack-trove/+bug/1308523

If I saw this as an operator before I adopted trove, I have a great deal of information about the quality of the packages.

I can use that to make a judgement call about whether I should try and package it myself, wait until the bug was fixed, or write trove off for this release.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:45:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@ttx, I don't see any value in forcing it into a binary application/nonapplication compared to the current (as you say) "metrics" approach  . Can you elaborate more on what the benefits would be?'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-06-04 07:43:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Tom,

On your example ... how will you deal with your tags considering that Ubuntu forgot to package trove-conductor in Icehouse, but Debian had it?'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-04 07:46:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for your question Thomas.

Basically, we'd mark the project with warning and have a link to the bug.

The important thing is that there is packaging badness. The actual distro doesn't matter too much.


As above - I'm actually thinking we should even consider removing the pkgtype attribute altogether - the purpose of this tag is not to be an exhaustive catalog of which projects are packaged in which distro+distroversions."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-04 07:53:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Another potential modification to this tag is to merge bug_link into the description. Does anyone have thoughts on that?'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-06-04 13:17:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Well, I certainly wouldn't like to have a "bad" attribute for packaging if there's a problem in another distribution than the one I'm working on. And opposite way: if my package is not in good shape, but there's a "good" tag because Ubuntu has it done correctly, it's no incentive to correct the Debian packaging. So unless you associate the package quality with a distribution, IMO it doesn't make sense.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-06-05 06:28:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Yeah, I'm pretty much dismayed that the operator tags team has decided to go off in a completely different direction than what the TC created tags for. This type of complex and schema'd information is going to lead to more problems than the current OpenStack wiki with regard to stale and wrong data.

These aren't tags. The repo should be renamed to "ops-docs-team" because that is what this is trying to be. IMHO, if operators are actually going to go through this much trouble (HIGHLY doubtful in my opinion that operators will keep this information either up-to-date or objective), then you might as well just contribute long-form documentation in the main docs project.

Sorry, I just am really disappointed in the direction here. Wish I had been at the summit session.

-jay'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-08 01:35:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for your comments Jay. So far, it looks like your main concerns are around the mechanism. I'd really appreciate your comments on the content - eg this tag is around packaging."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-08 01:37:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for your comments Thomas. I think they're valid, but I simply don't think we have enough resources to maintain an exhaustive list of the state of packaging in every single distribution+distro version. I feel like a general statement about packaging with links to prominent bugs is a reasonable compromise."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-06-08 02:32:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(8 comments)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-08 02:56:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Cheers Jay! I've put in one long comment that might make a few things make a bit more sense. I'll get to the others in a little bit."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-08 03:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-08 03:18:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

I think I got all of them now - let me know if I missed anything.'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-06-08 13:56:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Tom,

Again, if you say a package is in a bad general state because you are referencing a bug in *ONE* distribution, this is really bad. I fear that you're going to be very Ubuntu (or Red Hat) centric here, which I'd hate. So if you don't want to bother doing the actual work, then don't do such a tag at all please."}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2015-06-08 14:21:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thomas - I am sorry but I do not understand your comment. I would hope the package would be per platform (i.e. rpm / deb). I do not understand why this is Ubuntu/Redhat focused?'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-08 14:24:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add Ops:Packaged Tag

As discussed at the summit, a first simple tag to achieve would
be ops:packaged, which provides information to operators regarding
the existence and quality of packages for the project in distributions.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-ops-tags

Change-Id: Ie24ba41fabe439358f090cca4ec976c6eae48ef6

commit_message:
Flavor id should be the same as the last one when updating

When updating the flavor, horizon delete and recreate
a flavor according to the specified value.
At that time, horizon should specify the same value
as the previous value to flavor id.

Closes-Bug: #1502804
Change-Id: Ib3ecfcb3b04421d0a2bc2a77c78ff59ecac8cfb1

commit_message:
Remove gnocchi from the Dockerfiles

Gocchi doesn't and hasnt built.  Since we don't have an Ansible
implementation for Gnocchi, and the Dockerfiles don't build, this
patch removes Gnocchi from the system resulting in a clean build.

Since we use git we can always later revert this patch when we
are ready to tackle gnocchi as a technology.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: Iebbc536961fa9a29c0f5ed17d971234aa73b5bab
Closes-Bug: #1478145

commit_message:
Reject rule if assertion type unset

When the "type" of the remote rule is not present in the assertion this
should constitute a failure to match and reject the local change.

Conflicts:
	keystone/tests/unit/contrib/federation/test_utils.py
	keystone/tests/unit/mapping_fixtures.py

Change-Id: Idba9a95f31a28401b2d49545347175ee0f324ab5
Closes-Bug: #1487937
(cherry picked from commit 21b0c7e81691a513b7f6c39a71313ff06b957c94)

commit_message:
New optional_action_timer decorator

This adds a new optional_action_timer decorator for functions that may
or may not run an atomic action timer. This prevents lots of code
duplication.

Change-Id: I5a6c0a31085ffd7196384e396756bf241ab47ab4

commit_message:
Do not return None when get_attr if res is in SNAPSHOT/CHECK

To get attribute instead of return None if resource
is in SNAPSHOT or CHECK action.

This patch allow to get_attr for hot template version
'2013-05-23' also.

Change-Id: I318f4c158ebe0a4afbb3f0bcbe9d856d90f0a4bb
Closes-Bug: #1505054

(1 comment)

maybe not bad, move complexity away from a new-contributor building an all-in-one setup into maintenance of the dev utilities.

I think there used to be some idea that if you couldn't somehow manage to tough it through a few modifications to a couple of simple bash scripts that wrap some trivial basic *nix-y stuff like restarting services - then you're probably not going to be doing much swift development...

I'm not sure those old attitudes really hold up with current realities; but I think the more brains we push into minimizing the number of commands you have to copy and paste to get a swift-all-in-one setup on a vm the more questions it brings up on the value trade off trying to maintain the setup "documentation" vs. an automated build (e.g. https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one)

At least with an automated build you can automatically test it; but I think a more maintainable and flexible automated built tool eventually becomes even that much more less approachable for new contributors who probably honestly do benefit for a little "get your hands dirty" during their initial introduction to swift (I remember I did).

OTOH, maybe swapping a sed command for an if statement isn't really the last straw that pushes obfuscation through automation to it's breaking point ;)'}, {'account_id': 16896, 'date': '2015-10-12 20:41:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 16896, 'date': '2015-10-12 20:41:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add files to enable demo kuryr setup using Vagrant

These changes will help developers to quickly setup kuryr along with
docker, keystone and neutron using vagrantfile. Complete steps are
mentioned in ReadMe.

Change-Id: Ia2e16c13a9ae0a6c59991d205f055e3ae8b7b33f
Closes-Bug: #1504018

commit_message:
Add testresources and testscenarios used by oslo.db fixture

If we use oslo.db fixtures, we'll need these 2 packages or
the next version of oslo.db release will break us.

Change-Id: I7c0d2f6dabc20bd4ff0d29d3b47b948aa24ea56b
Closes-Bug: #1503501

commit_message:
Realizing SFC (2/5): Introducing alembic DB migration framework.

This patch implements alembic DB migration framework required by
networking-sfc repository for defining new data models and
realize Service Function Chaining (SFC) functionality in neutron.

Below changes are done as part of this patch-set:
 - Alembic migration framework for networking-sfc repository.
 - PEP8 changes for alembic migration check.
 - Devref document for user reference.

Co-Authored-By: Cathy Zhang <cathy.h.zhang@huawei.com>
Co-Authored-By: vikram.choudhary <vikram.choudhary@huawei.com>
Co-Authored-By: Louis Fourie <louis.fourie@huawei.com>

Change-Id: Iaa0335c54e368fc62a4dffca7f8cc43b88e89343

[{'created': '2015-10-13 01:43:01.000000000', 'message': 'Commit a6b516ae73d6671894a5cd3246e5db026b0e6505
Author: Laucon
Date: Mon Oct 12

Update "Chapter 1. Introduction to OpenStack High Availability in OpenStack High Availability Guide" to include HA concepts in context of OpenStack

Previously, the High Availability guide did not mention that High Availability is not the default set up for Open Stack. It did not mention that High Availability might not be for every user. I added that information and explained why High Availability is not the default set up and how it can be difficult to use in some cases.

Change-Id: Ic0495a2439885b1158ad8631537000684f3fb963
Closes-Bug: 1414115
'}]
commit_message:
Commit a6b516ae73d6671894a5cd3246e5db026b0e6505
Author: Laucon
Date: Mon Oct 12

Update "Chapter 1. Introduction to OpenStack High Availability in OpenStack High Availability Guide" to include HA concepts in context of OpenStack

Previously, the High Availability guide did not mention that High Availability is not the default set up for Open Stack. It did not mention that High Availability might not be for every user. I added that information and explained why High Availability is not the default set up and how it can be difficult to use in some cases.

Change-Id: Ic0495a2439885b1158ad8631537000684f3fb963
Closes-Bug: 1414115

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Iadcef8079efb8c94282c5cdefb91bfa3920f3919

Hi and thank you for your patch.
What we were doing recently is separating driver-specific client code from ironic into own projects. I'm referring to a pretty big oneview_client.py. By having it in a separate repo under your control you'd be able to move much faster. We've done with proliantutils for HP and we're in process of doing it for python-dracclient for DELL. Could you please consider doing the same thing here? Thanks."}, {'account_id': 10697, 'date': '2015-08-05 15:32:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

@Dimitry It's really a very good idea. Since we have some procedures to package that, could we do that after Liberty? Or is it really that show stopper?"}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-08-05 16:16:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: -Code-Review

It's not a real show-stopper for us, but it might become a show-stopper for you :) what I mean by that is that reviewing such a big patch requires considerable time and dedication from the team. You might have really easier time landing a smaller patch calling into your new library.

But of course I don't know about your internal procedures. I'm withdrawing my -1 and leaving it up to you."}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:56:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I was going to take a look at this, but I can't find the spec related to it. Is there a spec? Ok, I figured it out. The spec hasn't yet been approved (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/187762/).

I'm going to -2 this for now then, so I don't spend more time later trying to figure out the status of things. Folks can still review and comment and you can still push up new revisions. The -2 is to prevent it from being approved/merged.

Alternatively, you can put a 'Depends-on' tag or whatever in the commit message, to indicate that it depends on the spec being approved. Can this driver be based on the iscsi_ilo/agent_ilo driver so that you can use the Virtual media features and leverage all the iLO features implemented in that driver. 

Similarly you can use iLOPower and iLOManagement interfaces. The only difference in implementation would be in the proliantutils wherein OneView based implementaion should get called when OneView driver being used.

Also you can use the proliantutils to implement the OneView specific interfaces thereby simplifying these drivers and repetition of few things thata are already present in other iLO drivers.'}, {'account_id': 10697, 'date': '2015-09-01 13:46:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

Hello Shivanand, thanks for your review.

We did a thorough analysis of the iLO driver before opting to do a different implementation. Some of the reasons to do that are, mainly, not to use iLO directly and use OneView as a management layer. Single credentials are also a great difference in our context, besides we're not enforcing the same configurations as the iLO driver. Virtual Media isn't in our primary goal, but it is in our future roadmap (post Liberty).

You can find it in our already approved spec here: http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/ironic-specs/specs/approved/new-ironic-driver-for-oneview.html"}, {'account_id': 10697, 'date': '2015-09-01 13:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

commit_message:
OneView Driver for Ironic

This driver that will promote integration between Ironic and the HP OneView
Management System. The driver will allow Ironic to borrow non-dedicated servers
from OneViews's inventory to provision baremetal instances with minimal common
pre-configuration, set through OneView's *Server Profile Templates*.

Co-Authored-By: Alberto Barros <albertoffb@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Andr Aranha <afaranha@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Caio Oliveira <caiobo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Diego Pereira <diegolp@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Gabriel Bezerra <gabrielb@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Lilia Sampaio <liliars@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Sinval Vieira <sinval@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: Ic2fb7860e6b4f5183b6525ff7709c7616350a96a
Implements: blueprint new-ironic-driver-for-oneview
Depends-on: I914596e592477e148e642f93cfbe114464c3fe38

commit_message:
spec: Enable webmock connect to IPv4 link-local

compile and compile.with_all_deps rpsec matchers make
a call to all facts, and especially the ec2 one (this fact, try
to make a connection on the IPv4 link-local for ec2 metadata which
is incompatible with webmock restrictions), this seems to produce
random errors with puppet 3.{3,4}.x and facter 1.7.6.

Closes-bug: #1492636
Change-Id: If27fa1adca40bab7fdfcb0687b68d1524c961325

Update "Chapter 1. Introduction to OpenStack High Availability in OpenStack High Availability Guide" to include HA concepts in context of OpenStack

commit_message:
Avoids rebinding the same security group rules

Previously, logic has been introduced to ensure that all the given
security group rules have been applied. No need to force the rebinding
after the agent restarts.

Partial-Bug: #1505196

Change-Id: I355629ddb78441eaf2aadfd27efc6dd1f1ce4de9

commit_message:
Move security group setting to kubecluster.yaml

Currently security group is created for each kube masters and kube
minions. It's very redundant.
This patch moves security group setting to kubecluster.yaml to share.

Change-Id: Idb6cdb5c5c6015b29331238f7fbbcd92e1a70d83
Closes-Bug: #1499184

Caches VirtualSystemManagementService and MetricService

Sets the mentioned attributes as object attributes, as they
are constantly used and there is no need to instantiate them
every time.

commit_message:
Require oslo.cache 0.8.0

A symbol that keystone needs to switch to oslo.cache is available
as of the 0.8.0 release, so we need to bump the version in order
for keystone to switch to oslo.cache.

Change-Id: I7f9ec3331c913f890f8f7bbaf2bb9e3976aa62d8

commit_message:
make i local

This prevents bleed out of the i variable to other functions that
might call this inside their own iteration loop.

Change-Id: I42d0c287a6f4bb24ae3871de9abb7e0de98a8462

commit_message:
Updates requirements.txt and test-requirements.txt

Adds upper limit for oslo.log, as version 1.12.0 cannot be installed
on win32 systems, as pyinotify is not Windows specific.

Change-Id: I61348e0e48093b74858e6b4c03adae413bdff3ac

since we are screen scraping this is a clean solution.

commit_message:
add timing infrastructure to devstack

this adds a timing infrastructure to devstack to account for time
taken up by set of operations. The first instance of this is
accounting the time taken up by doing apt_get calls.

Change-Id: I855ffe9c7a75e9943106af0f70cf715c34ae25c5

commit_message:
Configure Ironic for Kubernetes load balancer feature

Kubernetes service provides the LoadBalancer feature

This is supported through an OpenStack plugin in Kubernetes code.
Enabling this features require configuring the cluster properly for
Kubernetes to interface with Neutron.  Kubernetes backend will then
create the Neutron load balancer pool, members, VIP and monitor,
and manage the pool members as pods are added/removed from the
service.

This patch updates the Ironic heat templates to adjust the minion
name and private network name to match what Kubernetes expects.

Additional scripts are from the patch for Fedora Atomic which
this patch has a dependency on.

Partially-Implements: blueprint external-lb
Change-Id: I74eaffe280b8ed20fce432d92fa6fc29048de8a5

commit_message:

The usage of assertEqual(False, ***) should be changed to a more
meaningful format of assertFalse(***).

Unauthed tests for Pools (Security)

These tests will attempt CRUD operations against Pools without
auth tokens. All requests should return 401 (Unauthorized).

[{'created': '2015-10-08 14:01:12.000000000', 'message': "Add heat template for restarting a stack

Use mistral workflow for checking status of the given stack and
recreate stack, if VM that belongs to the stack in ERROR state or

heat for successfull creation of a trust context.

Change-Id: I0b61177539c332db0833114e29eee7c74f2ff673
"}]
commit_message:
Add heat template for restarting a stack

Use mistral workflow for checking status of the given stack and
recreate stack, if VM that belongs to the stack in ERROR state or
doesn't exist. Note that it is needed to allow trusts delegation in
heat for successfull creation of a trust context.

Change-Id: I0b61177539c332db0833114e29eee7c74f2ff673

commit_message:
Bug fix for the openstack document "http://docs.openstack.org/draft/install-guide-rdo/neutron-controller-install-option2.html" under "configure the Linux bridge agent" from 'linuxbridge_agent.conf' to 'linuxbridge_agent.ini' # referenec: " https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/etc/neutron/plugins/ml2/linuxbridge_agent.ini"

Change-Id: I69290df211cc2f6e746e74a881e00aa6577e9884

commit_message:
Rename isolated creds to dynamic creds

Renaming the isolated_creds module to dynamic_creds module, and rename
the IsolatedCreds class to DynamicCredentialProvider in preparation
to migration to tempest-lib.

commit_message:
Make bootstrap-ansible script compatible with RHEL

This patch enables the bootstrap-ansible.sh script to also work on RHEL
and other "yum" based Linux distributions.

Change-Id: I3e28f4f4f09e7387c97afc219899bba1927215e8
(cherry picked from commit c03d6da8ecd3ffd225e18bd230bf006e2e80d84e)

commit_message:
Temporarily cap webob<1.5.0 in g-r to unblock nova

webob 1.5.0 has a change which breaks unit tests in nova, cinder
and manila.

If04eedb402092ca2cc307cb52f2231493c4375a2 fixes the nova change but
is blocked by the oslo.messaging 2.6.0 bug 1505295 which would be
fixed in I45189bb8d31819e55e2955b22aa1146257578d14 but that is
failing because of the webob failure, so we have multiple blocking
issues in nova.

Without squashing changes that we have to backport to stable/liberty
and muck with the history, we can pin both webob and oslo.messaging
versions in nova, merge that change, then land the fix for the unit
tests in nova for the webob bug, and then remove the cap on webob
here (hence the TODO).

Change-Id: I7a2197102bd812557b3a40d0a24e9a1363dd0dd7
Partial-Bug: #1505153

(10 comments)

Hi Sergey,

I have a few comments inline, thanks for your hard work here :) it's looking good.
However it is not good practice to pass patches with empty content. At the bare minimum, we require basic concept information to be included. I am marking this patch WIP - you will still be able to work on it and I will review again soon!

Please also address the niceness issue. It appears you are missing new lines at the end of the document and you're exceeding the maximum line length. Each line of text must be wrapped at 79 characters.

Thank you :)"}, {'account_id': 9162, 'date': '2015-09-28 04:59:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-2

Thanks,
Lana"}, {'account_id': 9377, 'date': '2015-09-28 09:05:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

[{'created': '2015-10-09 08:59:11.000000000', 'message': 'Fix run-aio-build.sh for curl one-liner

The developer documentation to run an AIO build includes a curl
one-liner to run the scripts/run-aio-build.sh script. However, due to
the way it sources other scripts it will fail to execute.

This change sources those scripts in a way to allow them to be run from
curl piped to bash and also from a local git checkout.

* In run-aio-build.sh it has cd to a fresh checkout so the path can be
  assumed and hard-coded.
* In bootstrap-aio.sh and bootstrap-ansible.sh we now test the existing
  behaviour first (which will work if you executed these scripts
  directly from a git checkout) or from a scripts subdirectory of the
  currrent path (which will work if you ran the curl one-liner).

Example of documentation which includes the curl one-liner:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-ansible/developer-docs/quickstart-aio.html#running-an-aio-build-in-one-step

The curl one-liner:
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openstack/openstack-ansible/master/scripts/run-aio-build.sh | sudo bash

Closes-Bug: #1504198
Change-Id: I2f8629f7cc4a1b650e8b5f6c6881168c0c5abde0
(cherry picked from commit c88534e16966f5f0b65183e584bb6cbd3058a26e)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix run-aio-build.sh for curl one-liner

The developer documentation to run an AIO build includes a curl
one-liner to run the scripts/run-aio-build.sh script. However, due to
the way it sources other scripts it will fail to execute.

This change sources those scripts in a way to allow them to be run from
curl piped to bash and also from a local git checkout.

* In run-aio-build.sh it has cd to a fresh checkout so the path can be
  assumed and hard-coded.
* In bootstrap-aio.sh and bootstrap-ansible.sh we now test the existing
  behaviour first (which will work if you executed these scripts
  directly from a git checkout) or from a scripts subdirectory of the
  currrent path (which will work if you ran the curl one-liner).

Example of documentation which includes the curl one-liner:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-ansible/developer-docs/quickstart-aio.html#running-an-aio-build-in-one-step

The curl one-liner:
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/openstack/openstack-ansible/master/scripts/run-aio-build.sh | sudo bash

Closes-Bug: #1504198
Change-Id: I2f8629f7cc4a1b650e8b5f6c6881168c0c5abde0
(cherry picked from commit c88534e16966f5f0b65183e584bb6cbd3058a26e)

commit_message:
Adding new test case to do heat yaml file validation

As we know the yaml file will change time to time, an validation test case
will help to reduce mistakes when changing yaml files.

Closes-Bug: #1504722

    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to

    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Remove auth headers in AuthProtocol

remove_auth_headers is the function that removes all the
HTTP_X_PROJECT_ID and similar authentication headers from an incoming
request so that you can't fake authentication to a service.

It turns out that we pass X-Project-Id and X-Domain-Id domain headers to
keystone for tokenless auth (and keystone doesn't use those headers
otherwise anyway) so if we want to use auth_token middleware in keystone
we only want to strip headers in the AuthProtocol subclass.

Change-Id: I5f0ea022156d0aaff4b3dc71c1cba981687723c9

commit_message:
Finally remove the global except handler

The global except handler has hidden problems for too long. Every typing
mistake would get caught and returned as a token validation failure.

Now it should only be catching errors from the online validation we can
narrow it further and say the only reason we should be putting invalid
statements in the cache is that there has been an actual validation
failure.

Change-Id: I42e6d8b673b7b92666bd3d9fd7910e6dee81d1ba

commit_message:
Add os-client-config functional testing

There's been a number of issues recently with not recognizing problems
in os-client-config problems until a release has been made. Run tempest
on every job.

Note that tempest itself won't tell us anything at all about
os-client-config. We just need the devstack part to complete and know it
was set up correctly.

Change-Id: Ic8a1d9877f89467c342d9a491886c9587d6f9a13
Related-bug: #1484373
Related-bug: #1496624

commit_message:
Add OpenFixture and get rid of 'open' mocks

This patch adds a new fixture that allows a specific
file to be mocked for 'open' calls while leaving the
normal 'open' behavior for everything else. This is to
prevent cases like the related bug where a library we
depend on can unexpectedly call 'open' on its own
(in that case it was debtcollector->warnings->linecache).

It also replaces all open mocks in the unit tests with
this new fixture.

Related-Bug: #1503847
Change-Id: Ie9e1a01acd5cb231718efd028d30df6c8dbcd3f0

commit_message:
Fix nested atomic action in VMTask scenario

In VMTask scenario, There are nested atomic actions.
 - vm.attach_floating_ip
    - nova.associate_floating_ip
 - vm.delete_floating_ip
    - nova.dissociate_floating_ip
But atomic actions should be removed.
So This patch fixed for nested atomic actions
by disabling atomic aciton in nova.XX_floating_ip.

Change-Id: I3c0e31c77c3181d8403c1a5570c78d2c7e9e5cf9
Closes-Bug: #1505074

commit_message:
Release oslo.db 3.0.0

Commit 30cb7372565e505e262b4f6b83f75ecf1f8a7f81 added the
oslo.db[fixtures] install target for getting the oslo.db test fixtures
code at runtime. Since this is a backward incompatible change it
triggers a major version bump

Changes since 2.6.0:

e00868d Fix coverage configuration and execution
97ed8f2 Add universal wheel tag to setup.cfg
340c425 No need for Oslo Incubator Sync
7a52dcf Updated from global requirements
52151ae Imported Translations from Zanata
b43844b Use stevedore directive to document plugins
b300f79 Make readme and documentation titles consistent
b49e181 Docstring fixes for enginefacade
14c955c Fix warnings in docstrings
0b3aee8 Autogenerate the module docs
6450edb Add config options to the documentation
7daffff Add support for pickling enginefacade context objects
680b59a Change ignore-errors to ignore_errors
d87228c Updated from global requirements
a705be9 Imported Translations from Zanata
e501a56 Handle case where oslo_db.tests has not been imported
30cb737 Move runtime test resources into setup.cfg [extras]

Change-Id: I51d2f6aa7345ca001858d97d300af6aedf637bec

commit_message:
Handle exceptions from plugins gracefully

If a tempest plugin is poorly constructed and raises an exception
during register_opts this can interfere with the rest of tempest
running correctly. This commit makes the tempest plugin handling
a bit more defensive so things don't crash if a plugin raises an
exception, instead the error is logged and tempest moves on.

Change-Id: Ic133eee1cced5ca3c53334d3d30c7b0b043ff789

commit_message:
Added shippable venv capabilities

This change allows the repo server to create all of the venvs
within its own server environment and provides the ability for all
of the target roles to download a prebuilt venv if one is available
else it will create them on the fly.

Change-Id: Ifce0e347e5dd5001549574589ab9b129c93c4345
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Add block of oslo.messaging 2.6.0

This is a temporary block of the oslo.messaging 2.6.0 release
to match an upstream block and to unblock the master branch.

Related-Bug: #1505295
Change-Id: Ib973d0f383f5b87913d58303573f297e892c82dc

commit_message:
Remove 'shared' from Neutron Firewall table

Neutron FWaaS firewall object does not support 'shared' attribute
at now and 'shared' attribute is not included in API response.
This commmit removes 'shared' attribute for firewall object.
For more detail of the background, please see the bug report.

Note that 'shared' attributes for firewall rule and policy
are supported. This commit only affect the firewall object.

(Pulled from gate, failing unit tests)

Change-Id: I5787529395e0005ce1efee48beb6f0f688c1c736
Closes-Bug: #1465440
(cherry picked from commit 991d8ac86c12fa45e1275851711d6feb2d9891a2)

commit_message:
Add __bool__ for classes that implement __nonzero__

__nonzero__ has been renamed to __bool__ in python3.4. So add the
__bool__ magic method that will in turn call the existing __nonzero__
method.

Change-Id: I3479564c57316733a9c30d97504ceac74771bfd4

commit_message:
handlers: make pyinotify really optional

Some platforms do not support it, so installing it unconditionnaly makes it
impossible to run project on other platforms than Linux.

Change-Id: I913d00dce16550aee393eb1e15819620f9fb937b

commit_message:
Add /status healthcheck endpoint.

Adds the /status endpoint. This endpoint will work as a helthcheck,
letting you know if application dependencies are set correctly. Right
now the only check made is related to the database availability.

Change-Id: I75351741f1e2ef44d808bf1b01f7d48ce39c03f1

commit_message:
Fixes target-project-id argument in zone transfer command

This patch makes target-project-id option as optional
in 'openstack zone transfer request create' command.

Change-Id: I98098d3263781c3517b4eb85ff5d1aeedb55a68f
Closes-Bug: #1499541

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:25:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Closes-bug: #1501987

This references the bug you're working on so reviewers can see what you've done and why."}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:32:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

What happened to simply removing the space before the \ in the second line?'}, {'account_id': 10607, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:37:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Sanjana,

Matt and I are confused by your change. The bug details that you only need to remove an extra space before "cloudarchive-liberty.list" in this command.

Please review.'}, {'account_id': 18691, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:45:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Matt and Alex.

I tried to run that code after removing the extra space too, but it still wasn't working. It gave me this error :
permission denied: /etc/apt/sources.list

That was because in the command:

sudo echo "deb http://ubuntu-cloud.archive.canonical.com/ubuntu" \
  "trusty-updates/liberty main" > \
  /etc/apt/sources.list.d/cloudarchive-liberty.list

when we use sudo in this fashion, the echo command is run as sudo but append command tries to open the file target as a non-sudo user. Hence, I made the proposed change.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:55:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Sanjana,

Congratulations on submitting your first patch! It's great to have your support.


To provide some context about our colleague's questions, in the install guide we have some general conventions - you can see them here: http://docs.openstack.org/draft/install-guide-ubuntu/common/conventions.html

One of those conventions is regarding the prompt usage.

Where we have

# command

we tell the user:
"""
The root user must run commands that are prefixed with the # prompt. You can also prefix these commands with the sudo command, if available, to run them.
"""


Implicit in this is that "it's up to the user to figure out how to use sudo" - we basically assume they have a root prompt.'}, {'account_id': 18691, 'date': '2015-10-07 03:04:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Tom.

I had read about those guidelines, but I was confused as to how to tell the user not to use the regular (sudo) approach to run this command but rather to run it as superuser? (sudo sh -c)

Should I add a comment or note in the documentation, highlighting this point, or leave it with only the following command in the document?

# echo "deb http://ubuntu-cloud.archive.canonical.com/ubuntu trusty-updates liberty main" >> /etc/apt/sources.list.d/cloudarchive-liberty.list'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-07 03:22:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Line length limitations with the DocBook publishing mechanism was the original reason for breaking up an otherwise single-line command into multiple lines. I think it pertained more to PDF than HTML output. We apparently carried the DocBook line length limitations into RST without further examination. Looking at the build of this patch, we may consider relaxing the limitation for code blocks. Tom? Lana?'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-10-07 10:47:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

+1 on extending line length. Please have a look at my inline comment regarding the command itself.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-07 12:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-10-07 12:47:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9162, 'date': '2015-10-08 00:08:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Sanjana, welcome to OpenStack docs!

There are three things you need to do to this patch to get it accepted at this point (please ask Alex for help if you need it):

1. Add the bug line ("Closes-Bug: #1501987") to your commit message
2. Leave the command as superuser (#, not $ sudo)
3. Remove the linebreaks from the command. These are here for historical reasons, and we can remove them.

Thanks,
Lana'}, {'account_id': 9162, 'date': '2015-10-08 00:09:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

To reply to Matt on linebreaks: yes, I think we can probably stop breaking on commands where it won't help readability. So things like URLs can probably be long, but I think breaking complicated commands with lots of switches is probably still a good idea."}, {'account_id': 18691, 'date': '2015-10-11 12:16:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-11 12:28:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Hi Tom and Alex.

I had already corrected that issue in the new patch set. Let  me see why is it showing a problem in that. In my local repository, I have used it as (#) root (not $ sudo), and then pushed here. 

Let me check again why the problem is still persisting. Really sorry for all the delay I am causing for to solve this bug.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-10-12 14:42:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Not a problem at all Sanjana. Git is an interesting tool.

In the mean time, let me tell you about one of the most handy features in git review. I break my repository all the time, and it saves me :)

Say we have a normal clone of the openstack-manuals repo, checked out on master:

git clone git://git.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-manuals.git

cd openstack-manuals


... then we wanted to download this patch (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/231799) to work on it.

You simply look at the number in the review URL (231799), and run:

git review -d 231799

to download the latest version of the patch from the code review system.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-12 19:41:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-12 19:42:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
[install] Fix the Ubuntu OpenStack package repo

Fix the step that adds the Ubuntu Cloud archive repository
for OpenStack packages.

Change-Id: I6ed6c1d8db45e92879d1d03629bce62891fb31e0
Closes-Bug: #1501987

commit_message:
Fix bad string replacement

In a previous patch, some bad string replacement messed up config
registration, causing error_cooldown to stop working.  This fixes it
and updates the instance_manager to inherit the RugTestBase, which
would have caught the issue in test.  This also requires a couple
of minor tweaks to existing tests.

Change-Id: I80a481d758e444b6146ef3597dd8f339bde9317c

'}, {'created': '2015-10-08 22:15:29.000000000', 'message': "Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I8d20b5297dde8a2ecfcaf3d21d221735bc9df8d6

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

It also fix proxy/ceilometer rspec syntax for Puppet 3.x. This change
could not be in a separated patchset since it's related to this patch.

Change-Id: I8d20b5297dde8a2ecfcaf3d21d221735bc9df8d6

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

It also fix proxy/ceilometer rspec syntax for Puppet 3.x. This change
could not be in a separated patchset since it's related to this patch.

Change-Id: I8d20b5297dde8a2ecfcaf3d21d221735bc9df8d6

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 597, 'name': 'Pete Zaitcev', 'email': 'zaitcev@kotori.zaitcev.us', 'username': 'zaitcev'}, {'_account_id': 2622, 'name': 'Samuel Merritt', 'email': 'sam@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'torgomatic'}, {'_account_id': 8122, 'name': 'Cyril Roelandt', 'email': 'cyril@redhat.com', 'username': 'cyril.roelandt.enovance'}, {'_account_id': 9107, 'name': 'Victor Stinner', 'email': 'vstinner@redhat.com', 'username': 'haypo'}, {'_account_id': 13052, 'name': 'SwiftStack Cluster CI', 'email': 'openstack-ci@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'swiftstack-cluster-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 14867, 'name': 'Jaivish Kothari(janonymous)', 'email': 'janonymous.codevulture@gmail.com', 'username': 'Janonymous'}]

[{'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:50:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:54:02.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from unicode to py3'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:38:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This change was fully generated by the sixer tool.

I reviewed this change in Gerrit: it looks good to me. It only does one thing: replace expr.next() with next(expr).

On Python 2, this change is 100% safe: next(expr) does exactly one thing, it calls expr.next().

On Python 3, there is a low risk that some objects implement a next() method for Python 2, but no __next__() method for Python 3, and so next(obj) will fail. It's *not* a problem: it can be fixed later by adding missing __next__ methods (adding "__next__ = next" is enough in fact). But only the class definition will have to be modified, not all call sites. I expect that very few classes don't declare __next__ (I saw that Swift is quite good to define next and __next__).

(I will not vote +1, it's my own change.)'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:51:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Quite obvious, thanks.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:51:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
py3: Replace gen.next() with next(gen)

The next() method of Python 2 generators was renamed to __next__().
Call the builtin next() function instead which works on Python 2 and
Python 3.

The patch was generated by the next operation of the sixer tool.

Change-Id: Id12bc16cba7d9b8a283af0d392188a185abe439d

This replaces: Ibca7240efe705c35bf7a17898caba5a4531bc858

Changes include:
  - Support for the list/search/get methods.
  - Fixes a bug in user create.
  - Allow updating user name and some keystone v3 attributes.
  - delete_user() method is aligned to return True if the
    delete succeeded, False if the user was not found.

commit_message:
Align users with list/search/get interface

This replaces: Ibca7240efe705c35bf7a17898caba5a4531bc858

Changes include:
  - Support for the list/search/get methods.
  - Fixes a bug in user create.
  - Allow updating user name and some keystone v3 attributes.
  - delete_user() method is aligned to return True if the
    delete succeeded, False if the user was not found.
  - Test all the things.

Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>

Change-Id: I2f1296a0247ad33e5cb6b2d67559165a55592fd3

commit_message:
Remove incomplete shared filesys option diffs

The Shared File Systems chapter in the config-ref
has a place-holder for a new, updated and deprecated
options page. This currently shows incomplete info and
TODOs. It needs to be fixed or removed.

This commit removes the page.

Change-Id: Ie50f360fac9c1e9859948fa1b45432fe0648b76a
Partial-Bug: #1503933

commit_message:
Download forbidden when get_image_location is set.

When using v2 an attempt to download an image would return a 403 if the
get_image_location policy was set.

Note: We had been returning both 404 and 204 when no data was
available. There was no way to detect the 404 case without trying to
access the image locations so I've standardized on 204.

Change-Id: I658b08a35d3a8cb8a7096baf716ccb3d6e7d9abf
Closes-bug: 1501672
(cherry picked from commit b47f625443c3b46483506926f31fee42478705d4)

commit_message:
Use pip install --proxy when $HTTPS_PROXY is set

During execution of our bootstrap scripts, we need to install some
packages before we have constructed any of the infrastructure. In
this case when installing behind a proxy we should respect that
proxy.

When $HTTPS_PROXY is not set but $HTTP_PROXY is, that will be used
instead. The use of trusted-host or other pip configurations to
enable this usage are out of scope and can be resolved separately.

Change-Id: I3df5ef6a7d33a3357e8c00f138b019c06c6bc3d6
Closes-Bug: 1504405
(cherry picked from commit a875596ba2a0c37fff131ff6ea1f899732b0f5ce)

commit_message:
Add a default config file location to the api

This commit adds a default config file location at
/etc/openstack-health.conf. If a conf file path isn't provided on the
cli the api process will default to reading the config file at
/etc/openstack-health.conf, this will let us deploy the api in
scenarios where we don't have the ability to pass arguments.
The cli args method can only be used when invoking the server through
the dev/test flask test server directly, if deploying for real you
need to use /etc/openstack-health.conf for the config file.

Change-Id: I7de91197dacbec3f5b0917c27fda72b4366d37e4

commit_message:
Add support for specifying swift ring directory range

We plan to allow specification of the range of directories to be
used when building the Swift rings. The range will be specified
using the bash curly brace format where the range starts with 0
or 1:  <root>{(0|1)..<end of range>}. <root> is the root name used
for the directories.  In future, we will want to mount individual
devices under the specified directories.

This element change supports the planned specification format.  It
also works with existing device lists contained in overcloud yaml
templates.  If this change is accepted there is a corresponding
Swift overcloud yaml template change which we will submit.

The yaml template change will check that the range specifier
submitted when creating the corresponding overcloud stack conforms
with the format outlined above.

Change-Id: I319baf471b902ba39196a17ce27746a8bd5f87ae

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-25 00:38:20.000000000', 'message': "Add support for hash-based RUG scale out

This adds support for running multiple RUG processes to scale out
and distribute appliance load across them.  It uses a hash ring implementation
lifted from Ironic (with modification).  The gist is:

* Workers now maintain a copy of the hash ring, which is hashed using the
list of members in the cluster.

* A new subprocess connects to an external coordination service via tooz, ie
memcache or zookeeper.  This service's only purpose is to track cluster
membership and report changes to this subprocess.  On membership changes,
the coordination subprocess creates a REBALANCE event and puts it on the
internal notification queue.  There is no leadership election required.

* When a worker gets a REBALANCE event, it rebalances the hash ring based
on the new membership list.

* Prior to processing any events bound for a specified router, the worker
first checks the hash manager to find if the resource is assigned to it.
If not, it ignores it.  If it is, it processes the event.

Change-Id: I8d04100ffc0e2f2223ebf4b079551dac99224344

commit_message:
Add support for hash-based RUG scale out

This adds support for running multiple RUG processes to scale out
and distribute appliance load across them.  It uses a hash ring implementation
lifted from Ironic (with modification).  The gist is:

* Workers now maintain a copy of the hash ring, which is hashed using the
list of members in the cluster.

* A new subprocess connects to an external coordination service via tooz, ie
memcache or zookeeper.  This service's only purpose is to track cluster
membership and report changes to this subprocess.  On membership changes,
the coordination subprocess creates a REBALANCE event and puts it on the
internal notification queue.  There is no leadership election required.

* When a worker gets a REBALANCE event, it rebalances the hash ring based
on the new membership list.

* Prior to processing any events bound for a specified router, the worker
first checks the hash manager to find if the resource is assigned to it.
If not, it ignores it.  If it is, it processes the event. This also applies
to incoming command events.

Partially implements: blueprint rug-scaling

Change-Id: I8d04100ffc0e2f2223ebf4b079551dac99224344

commit_message:
tox: add a generic environment to build a RST guide

With this environment it is possible to build a single RST guide with
the following common: tox -e build -- NAME

E.g. to build the contributor guide run the following command:

tox -e build -- contributor-guide

Change-Id: I94cf504eece14b2b8d2734cb5b4c16a1b409026f

commit_message:
Fix mesos build image error

According to https://mesosphere.com/downloads/
the ubuntu 14.04 need java8 requirements. And
at the same time, we not want to use oracle jdk,
use openjdk directly. Check this for openjdk further:
https://github.com/Azure/azure-quickstart-templates/
pull/685/files

Change-Id: I30d5be40882b2a5a20ee537d27bcfaa0df531925
Closes-Bug: #1505078

- gate-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-ceph http://logs.openstack.org/82/232082/1/check-tripleo/gate-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-ceph/bc372fd/ : FAILURE in 2h 47m 51s (non-voting)
- gate-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-ha http://logs.openstack.org/82/232082/1/check-tripleo/gate-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-ha/106c2c4/ : SUCCESS in 1h 37m 15s (non-voting)
- gate-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/82/232082/1/check-tripleo/gate-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f21puppet-nonha/e00ea6c/ : SUCCESS in 1h 28m 59s'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-10-08 12:39:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I would rather see us require these settings because there isn't a good default.

I don't (ever) use the default 'baremetal' default for example (I use custom flavors because I have multiple hardware types). Also, I think it is quite easy to control these via the tooling, or an extra environment.

Just my preference here..."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:01:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> I would rather see us require these settings because there isn't a good default.

There is a good default - we align with what's in the docs (which is baremetal), because that's what most folks (particularly new users and contributors) will be using.

I accept that for advanced users (yourself included), these aren't good defaults, but nearly everyone else will find this default actually works.

My motivation is to reduce the (large) number of repeated parameters required to deploy direct via heat on the standard development environment (what is deployed via tripleo.sh for developers, and used in CI).

Forcing everyone to specify what's in the docs is basically very inconvenient.  It's also fragile because we then duplicate the docs parameters in tripleoclient (and the UI, or anywhere else that calls TripleO), all because we have defaults that don't work for anyone in the templates."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-10-08 15:55:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

i agree these are the right and good defaults. i dont really think its arguable that these defaults dont work the vast majority of the time. defaults are exactly that...defaults. Saying it's won't work for a few isn't a reason to remove them.

This point, taken into consideration with the tripleoclient patches to remove defaults makes me -2 on removing the defaults from the templates unless we're going to offer a default environment or equivalent, committed to tripleo-heat-templates or maybe tripleo-common directly, and CI/tripleo.sh updated to use that. But, what I'm really opposed to is requiring people to hand write more environment files. That's not manageable."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-09 07:36:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@James: I think we're in agreement then.  My argument is basically that we should set the template defaults to match the docs, and that should align with what tripleoclient requires (for the default "no options" case, which aligns with the default/basic documented workflow).

Then, we can remove the hard-coded defaults everywhere else (e.g in tripleoclient), and rely on environment/enable_foo.yaml to pull in optional non-default configurations.

This all started when I tried to deploy direcly via Heat, bypassing tripleoclient.  I was really shocked at how many non-optional or conflicting parameters there were.  It's not a good experience for anyone IMHO.'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:11:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

just to clarify my earlier comment.

i think this patch series is fine (haven't reviewed the rest all that closely yet), but i'm fine with the intended direction.

my main thing though is that we should somehow offer sane defaults (by sane, I mean what we test with in tripleo-ci and document). Right now, those are hardcoded in tripleoclient, which doesn't seem right. So, whether we move them to the templates (as this patch series does), or we move them to a pre-canned environment file, both would be positive steps IMO.

If we do use the environment file, I'd just like to see it documented really well so it's obvious that to get a "base" working deployment, this is the environment file you'd use, etc.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:24:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-10-12 17:23:15.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Giving up on this, going to try the environment file approach and removing all the defaults we can't agree on."}]

Currently only the CephStorage role defaults to "baremetal", but in
the default deployment documented in tripleo-docs, we expect all
nodes to use this Flavor.  So update the default such that clients
don't necessarily have to provide it for default setups.

commit_message:
Update Flavor defaults and descriptions

Currently only the CephStorage role defaults to "baremetal", but in
the default deployment documented in tripleo-docs, we expect all
nodes to use this Flavor.  So update the default such that clients
don't necessarily have to provide it for default setups.

This makes it easier e.g if you want to create an overcloud direct
via heatclient or some other tool that's not tripleoclient which
hard-codes these defaults internally.

Change-Id: Id53c8a629b4191ab5bae116a6f81ec71be5126a8

Similar to the flavors I'm not convinced there is a good default for these so why change them?

> Similar to the flavors I'm not convinced there is a good default for these so why change them?

*All* our docs refer to the openstack-full workflow, so if you follow our documentation, these are the values we need.

I accept that for alternate implementations these will be different, but it makes no sense to have defaults which won't ever work for *any* of our supported implementations.

Giving up on this, going to try the environment file approach and removing all the defaults we can't agree on."}]

commit_message:
Switch Image parameters to default to openstack-full

The default documented deployment now uses a common openstack-full
image, so it's more convenient if we align the template defaults
with this image.

Change-Id: Ia619c3114df0dfb586b1409ab9e18660cd37c1a5

commit_message:
fix for systemd based rabbitmq guest

Upstart seemed to be providing output from rabbitmqctl, which we
were depending on to tell whether rabbit was up, but systemd does
not do this. Changing the status check to use rabbitmqctl instead
so that status check works for both systemd and upstart.

Also moved the command to enable the management console to after
rabbitmq startup since the command was failing if rabbit was not
up.

Change-Id: I5f0c277a3201911b0bc998ff7f17d526dab6b33e

commit_message:
Reorganize parameters per service and role

As a precursor to introducing parameter groups, reshuffle the parameters
so we have
* common/global parameters
* common service parameters (e.g RPC and DB settings)
* Per-service options for deployed services
* Per-role options for the deployed nodes
* Parameters associated with updates

Hi there.  I'm not sure whether this is the correct forum for this, but I was seeing some startup problems with the CentOS keystone container due to Apache startup failure.  I narrowed the problem down to leftover state files in /var/run/httpd.

This patch clears out /var/run/httpd on container startup, but I don't think what I've done is the best way to do it.  I'm happy to rewrite based on feedback as I'm a bit of a newcomer to the kolla project.

commit_message:
Update NeutronDhcpAgentsPerNetwork to align with ControllerCount

In tripleoclient we correlate the NeutronDhcpAgentsPerNetwork with the
number of controllers, capped to 3.  So given that the template
defaults the ControllerCount to 1, 1 seems like a more consistent
value for NeutronDhcpAgentsPerNetwork, and it's consistent with
python-tripleoclient.

Change-Id: I04ada4a3fc0ec5f234139b67a6d1c3103d565666

commit_message:
Introduce DEFAULT_SERVICE_REGIONS

It should be together with related change in django-openstack-auth, if
specified it will change the default service region calculation: it
will be taken from this setting (on a per-endpont basis) instead of a
value stored in cookies.  This value is still checked for sanity,
i.e. it should be present in Keystone service catalog.

Change-Id: I0f8c35337c837c137c07e07d9aae3e591e5e2333
Partial-bug: #1452722

commit_message:
Enable H234 check (assertEquals is deprecated, use assertEqual)

All usages of assertEquals and assertNotEquals are fixed now, so let's enable
the H234 check to avoid regressions in the future.

Change-Id: I2c2ccb3b268cf9eb11f2db045378ab125a02bc31

commit_message:
Corrected wrong url in router detail page

In router detail page, the link to the network detail page
redirecting to admins panel. so the non admin users not
able to access the network detail page from router detail page.

Change-Id: If6d70dcb214b9557d8501b9252b75fbfd9add248
Closes-Bug: #1504123

commit_message:
Heat Stacks Details: Events table doesn't show up

It shows a loading sign.
There is an AttributeError because event_list does not return
with any 'resource_type' to map. Since it doesn't make any sense,
removed the resource_to_url link, and also add a check in the method.

Change-Id: Ic94cffaa2450bbee3f9c9dabcaffb03a6cdc3b46
Closes-Bug: #1493216

commit_message:
Fixing template filtering by plugin name

Filtering the node group templates and cluster templates
tables by plugin was failing because it was using the
incorrect field name.  It has now been updated to search
against "plugin_name", which is correct.

Change-Id: I41760fa9cfa714cf1c9ae90229cb48ff759289fc
Closes-Bug: #1503235

commit_message:
Recommend enabling NTPD in the documenation

Without NTPD, rabbitmq reconnects often and generally causes havoc
in an OpenStack installation.

Change-Id: I7911d115312132a156331f61b8c320c32ddc798c

commit_message:
Separated UI and Configuration Logic

This removes the use of UI components from the openstack library,
making it reusable outside of ironic-webclient. It is mainly achieved by
removing the addLocal invocation of $modal from $$configuration, nad
moving the ConfigurationAddController from the openstack module
to the ironic root application module. Tests for the
ConfigurationAddController have been also added, and the test
threshold has been raised accordingly.

Change-Id: Icfd7504be966cee330a934c99b50465fd8ff7993

  'stderr_str',
  'stderr_len',
  'exit_code', instead of just stdout string
* 'run_on_remote' wrapper leaved for compatibility

commit_message:
[stable/7.0]Improve 'run_on_remote' for more general use

Author: Maksym Strukov
To use method in cases when ec is expected to be not zero and reduce
duplicated code in asserts messages new parameters in 'run_on_remote'
method proposed with following logic:
* 'assert_ec_equal' with default '[0]'. Error message will be logged only
when exit_code != assert_ec_equal. Can pass xrange(1,8) or [1, 4, 5]
* 'raise_on_assert' with default 'True'. Exception now can be
surpressed when exit_code != assert_ec_equal if 'raiseOnAssert' is 'False'

Also:
* 'run_on_remote_get_results' return dict with:
  'command',
  'host',
  'stdout',
  'stdout_str',
  'stdout_len',
  'stdout_json', if jsonify=true
  'stderr',
  'stderr_str',
  'stderr_len',
  'exit_code', instead of just stdout string
* 'run_on_remote' wrapper leaved for compatibility

Change-Id: I32a9d743929d01857a88844976074df719d9880a
Closes-Bug: #1489165
(cherry picked from commit 32b6bc8cea5c595aa92e2c2c825762b53c49e191)

commit_message:
Refactor: change 403 status codes in test names

Change I952cac73a9713bde4ad757371ca8b4ded93f207e refactored the keystone test
cases to use the six.moves.http_client for HTTP status codes instead of
integers. This change refactors the method names to follow the same pattern.

Change-Id: I90b17a7196075c164fe8bbd0f43af13a118e4c7e

commit_message:
Add 'deactivated' status to image schema.

New 'deactivated' status was introduced in Kilo release,
but it doesn't listed in available image statuses in the schema.

It leads to issues  on the client side, when it can't validate
the image with this status against the schema and returns the error.

Change-Id: I5ec264614ae7ecf54b846ad0600442a18c61d24c
Closes-bug: #1505218
Related-bug: #1505134

(1 comment)

If user build image using `build.py -n 172.22.2.81:4000`, kolla-ansible can't pull these images. The image name generated from build.py using `build.py -n 172.22.2.81:4000` looks like 172.22.2.81:4000/data.

But the image name kolla-ansible pull looks like 172.22.2.81:4000//data.

This is why I update the document."}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-10-12 13:42:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I see now, thanks for the explanation!'}, {'account_id': 13747, 'date': '2015-10-12 14:04:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

By the way, the root of the problem is that the meaning of the namespace in build.py is different from the meaning of the namespace in globals.yml. That make user confuse and mistake easily. I file a bug to try to solve it. I need more feedback. commit_message:
[Docker] Do not try to delete container on destroyed host

When Environment get deleted both Docker/k8s host and
Docker applications get deleted. So it is possible that host
will try to delete container from an Instance that was already
destroyed. Attempt to send commands to such instance
will hang until timeout because there is no more agent
exist on the other side.

Change-Id: Ia6e8064ae50c24ce595ed08e446ed45b96b4a330
Closes-Bug: #1504623
Depends-On: I298f3f079a153ef87ed7213b7f1432c9e5e4b4b6

commit_message:
Improve saving confirmation dialog

- If there is validation error, do not allow to save changes
- If saving failed, show error message instead of closing
  the dialog silently

Change-Id: I4e849d21eca429b7bd3b9ad0edeb6e3d4113f855
Closes-Bug: #1484530

commit_message:
Do not try to delete server from deleted Heat stack

Because now Environment's .destroy method would
be called before that of an Instance the later will try
to delete itself from the stack that is physically not
existing and represented as an empty dictionary in
HeatStack.current().

With this change Instance will check stack existence
before deleting anything.

Also a method to check if Instance is present in Heat
stack template was added so that application could check
if it is safe to use the instance (for example to send Agent plans)

Change-Id: I298f3f079a153ef87ed7213b7f1432c9e5e4b4b6
Closes-Bug: #1503715

[{'created': '2015-10-12 13:47:00.000000000', 'message': 'Add script to document deleting private networks

commit_message:
Add script to document deleting private networks

In order to test clouds with no private networks, we need to delete
the ones made by devstack. This is how that works.

Change-Id: I6c9d4d62ea34372d53399aa2b8b27b762d53339b

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes, the
init.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize all
logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place

Change-Id: Ia040f7c935941da0b747cf3e8b5eda1abf2ae07a
