commit_message:
Add agent_amt driver

This combines the AgentDeploy deploy driver with the AMT power and
management drivers, to allow the agent-based deploy mechanism on AMT
hardware.

Co-Authored-By: Devananda van der Veen <devananda.vdv@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1499489
Implements: blueprint agent-amt-driver
Change-Id: Ideaa68d97477a9a924c33e76b4da3aa8fb02f503

commit_message:
Don't assume that $i variable won't be overriden in extras.d plugins

This causes an incorrect warning about ironic jobs putting an unexpected
file in extras.d.

Change-Id: I57acf91fba3fe13b3cc8dd739034e146a0b237c4

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in
Keystone's Liberty release:
 - keystone-paste.ini
 - policy.json

The following defaults have their values changed in order to accommodate
Keystone's configuration method for the Liberty release. Note that any
user_variables.yml values that have been set to customise these will need
to be reviewed and adjusted accordingly for liberty.
 - keystone_identity_driver
 - keystone_token_driver
 - keystone_token_provider
 - keystone_revocation_driver
 - keystone_assignment_driver
 - keystone_resource_driver
 - keystone_ldap_identity_driver

DocImpact

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated source in
Keystone's Liberty release:
 - keystone-paste.ini
 - policy.json

The following defaults have their values changed in order to accommodate
Keystone's configuration method for the Liberty release. Note that any
user_variables.yml values that have been set to customise these will need
to be reviewed and adjusted accordingly for liberty.
 - keystone_identity_driver
 - keystone_token_driver
 - keystone_token_provider
 - keystone_revocation_driver
 - keystone_assignment_driver
 - keystone_resource_driver
 - keystone_ldap_identity_driver

The patch changes the endpoint registration to be versionless, and also
sets the default API version to be used by all services to the v3 API.

commit_message:
Update Keystone Configuration for Liberty

This patch includes the following updates based on the updated
source in Keystone's Liberty release:
 - keystone-paste.ini
 - policy.json

The following defaults have their values changed in order to
accommodate Keystone's configuration method for the Liberty release.
Note that any user_variables.yml values that have been set to
customise these will need to be reviewed and adjusted accordingly
for Liberty.
 - keystone_identity_driver
 - keystone_token_driver
 - keystone_token_provider
 - keystone_revocation_driver
 - keystone_assignment_driver
 - keystone_resource_driver
 - keystone_ldap_identity_driver

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Change-Id: Ib6f6c933c5d300057926143c9aa964bac292be08

commit_message:
Tidy up plugin list in 'bandit -h' output

Make the list of plugins included in the Bandit help output nicer
to read by adding \n\t's and disabling argparse line wrapping.

Change-Id: I28db0fce2b0a95dd949240933a5be0ddd0a6ef21
Closes-Bug: #1505163

commit_message:
Update settings during deploying an IBMi VM.

IBMi VM depends on tagged io, ipl source and keylock position to determine
PowerOn mode. During deploying an new IBMi VM, tagged io, IPL source and
keylock position must be set. This change set will add a new task in
spawn flow to set those required attributes for IBMi.
Change-Id: Idd5a305ff9aa6de11920fbc61099a10a0b2df748

commit_message:
Allow one to specify horizon ALLOWED_HOSTS

If horizon is running in production (DEBUG is False), it will answer
only to the IPs/hostnames specified in the ALLOWED_HOSTS variable in the
local_settings.py configuration file.

The puppet-horizon module offer the feature to customize that,
tripleo-heat-teamplates was missing the link between the top-level
parameter and the puppet parameter, hence this commit.

More info :

 * https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/settings/#allowed-hosts
 * https://github.com/openstack/puppet-horizon/blob/master/templates/local_settings.py.erb#L14-L24

Change-Id: I5faede8b74a0318e15baa761dc502b95b051ae0d

commit_message:
Code refactor for generating integer in testcase

This will remove the need of import random in unit/objects/test_base.py
as its already done in tests/tools.py and some of the functions are
called from there.

Closes-Bug: #1504125

commit_message:
[test runner] Support --config-file option

Previously, if --config-file option was provided, it was not applyed
since CONF variable was not initialized.

Change-Id: I3f8d860d3f974e89190bdfd5b2c2be1c464d2ec7
Closes-Bug: #1504125

Add dependent application test

- Add Lighttpd app for test, which depends on UpdateExecutor
- Add test with application dependencies

Partially-implements: blueprint dependent-apps-and-ssc-tests
Co-Authored-By: Dmytro Dovbii <ddovbii@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Change the way devstack configures murano-dashboard

Due to change in horizon settings file, we need to change
the method of murano-dashboard configutration. Murano dashboard lib
will now put config into local_settings.py file of Horizon.

Change-Id: Ibeab0e65c82eccb31a39373cdc2de5e409087806
Closes-Bug: #1505208

Remove [H405] and [H404] ignoring in tox.ini

commit_message:
Moving rsyslog to librarian

This change moves the rsyslog module to librarian. This change also
updates the rsyslog module to v3.5.1 from our customized 1.1.4 version.
With the update, our usage of file resources to manage syslog
configuration files has also been updated to leverage the
rsyslog::snippet resource.

This change also cleans up the lint issues with the openstack::logging
class.

Partial blueprint: fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I6734f8415940c5b1869eca442ce72534db8ff3d2

commit_message:
Adding MAINTAINERS to fuel-upgrade

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.
Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/1

Change-Id: If492a8fa12d83a6fa256c387d296d48c4cc450d1
Co-Authored-By: Mike Scherbakov <mscherbakov@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Replace image property 'is-public' on 'visibility'

Since liberty glance client uses v2 glance-api version and there is
no such property 'is-public'. It is replaced on 'visibility'.

Change-Id: I9ac535a0eecba0ecc890a020677dc86e8c000df1
Related-bug: #1503790

commit_message:
minut: port ClientException tweaks from swiftclient; dict .pop

openstack/python-swiftclient@5ae4b423 changed python-swiftclient's
ClientException to have its http_status attribute default to
None (rather than 0) and to use super in its __init__ method. For
consistency's sake, it's nice for Swift's inlined copy of
ClientException to receive the same patch. Also, the retry function in
direct_client (a major user of ClientException) was using a somewhat
awkward conditional-assignment-and-delete construction where the .pop
method of dictionaries would be more idiomatic.

Change-Id: I70a12f934f84f57549617af28b86f7f5637bd8fa

commit_message:
rest: Always return complete exceptions.

On 400, instead of sometime returning the indexer exception
and sometimes just a raw 404.

This change raises everywhere indexer exceptions.

Change-Id: Ieb8b3f916556528d7a2db2020d5d0e36d91ad332

[{'created': '2015-10-12 11:30:30.000000000', 'message': "make i local in run_phase

We were getting some spill over because i might have a value which
isn't related. This should shield us from that.

Change-Id: I798630edf832a4e930d65853d48b0bab529c5a1e
"}, {'created': '2015-10-12 11:35:16.000000000', 'message': "use less generic variable for iteration

Using i for iteration is dangerous if you do a ``source`` inside the
function, because it means someone else's non localized use of i might
change that value later. This happens in the ironic case.

Change-Id: I798630edf832a4e930d65853d48b0bab529c5a1e
"}]
commit_message:
use less generic variable for iteration

Using i for iteration is dangerous if you do a ``source`` inside the
function, because it means someone else's non localized use of i might
change that value later. This happens in the ironic case.

Change-Id: I798630edf832a4e930d65853d48b0bab529c5a1e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-12 09:31:27.000000000', 'message': "metadata: don't crash proxy on non-unicode user data

We attempt to log every successful metadata response with LOG.debug. But
as per oslo.log docs [1], we should make sure that what we pass into the
library is unicode.

Http.request returns a tuple of Response object and a string, which is
bytes in Python 2.x [2].

That's why we need to convert the response content to unicode before
passing it into oslo.log.

To achieve it, we utilize encodeutils.safe_decode with 'replace' errors
handling strategy, so that we don't get exceptions on input that does
not conform unicode.

For the unit test case, we pass a string that is not expected to convert
to unicode with errors='strict' strategy or similar, and check that we
still don't crash.

While at it, we remove a check for the number of log calls being
triggered, because it's something that we should avoid validating in
test cases, and it cannot trigger a real bug. The mock that was used to
count the number would also hide the bug that we try to reproduce.

Note that the bug does not require debug to be set because the crash
occurs before oslo.log machinery decides it should not log the message.

[1]: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.log/usage.html#no-more-implicit-conversion-to-unicode-str
[2]: http://bitworking.org/projects/httplib2/doc/html/libhttplib2.html#httplib2.Http.request

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/metadata/namespace_proxy.py
	neutron/tests/unit/agent/metadata/test_namespace_proxy.py

commit_message:
metadata: don't crash proxy on non-unicode user data

We attempt to log every successful metadata response with LOG.debug. But
as per oslo.log docs [1], we should make sure that what we pass into the
library is unicode.

Http.request returns a tuple of Response object and a string, which is
bytes in Python 2.x [2].

That's why we need to convert the response content to unicode before
passing it into oslo.log.

To achieve it, we utilize encodeutils.safe_decode with 'replace' errors
handling strategy, so that we don't get exceptions on input that does
not conform unicode.

For the unit test case, we pass a string that is not expected to convert
to unicode with errors='strict' strategy or similar, and check that we
still don't crash.

While at it, we remove a check for the number of log calls being
triggered, because it's something that we should avoid validating in
test cases, and it cannot trigger a real bug. The mock that was used to
count the number would also hide the bug that we try to reproduce.

Note that the bug does not require debug to be set because the crash
occurs before oslo.log machinery decides it should not log the message.

[1]: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.log/usage.html#no-more-implicit-conversion-to-unicode-str
[2]: http://bitworking.org/projects/httplib2/doc/html/libhttplib2.html#httplib2.Http.request

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/metadata/namespace_proxy.py
	neutron/tests/unit/agent/metadata/test_namespace_proxy.py

Closes-Bug: #1501772
Change-Id: I6a32c40ff117fae43913386134c8981539697ce8
(cherry picked from commit 80e3d9be4923ecad17377b1d15c8392b8a43dac6)
(cherry picked from commit 118a76fd651c19ad098cdee9d0a122a00ddc4e3b)

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes,
the init.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize
all logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place.

Change-Id: I41ad2ed3b75d8e939f47a465b191a2b99694f18a

subject: Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes, the init.pp and the
logging.pp classes.

This review aims to centralize all logging related parameters in a
single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place

Change-Id: I1132395295f542f4ba5459769a5b4b829a9cd7a7

subject: Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes, the init.pp
and the logging.pp classes.

This review aims to centralize all logging related parameters in a single class,
the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir
  * log_file

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place

Change-Id: Ic268104fd9bc77bc142fc635285b0459f3d4314f

commit_message:
Support vnic_type, vif_type filters in ml2 port list

portbinding:vnic_type and portbinding:vif_type filters
are presently not supported in ml2 plugin when the
client calls 'neutron port-list'.

This patch supports these filters in the ml2 plugin
_ml2_port_result_filter_hook function.

Change-Id: I514e3b30bc03e17f6e00cd33ce9f42d33f8bb2f5
Closes-bug: #1391806

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes, the
init.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize all
logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir
  * log_file

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place.

Change-Id: I2ad392f8f12be3f3a7d51916e0645531ed1184a2

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes,
the api.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize
all logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir
  * log_file

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place.

Change-Id: I9f69d50020c703115625fdcc62708dc57dd465ce

commit_message:
Resync L3, DHCP and OVS agents upon revival

In big and busy clusters there could be a condition when
rabbitmq clustering mechanism synchronizes queues and during
this period agents connected to that instance of rabbitmq
can't communicate with the server and server considers them
dead moving resources away. After agent become active again,
it needs to cleanup state entries and synchronize its state
with neutron-server

Closes-Bug: #1505166
Change-Id: I44b7b9fcbcab9330dd645ce876c743b3eaf74c8c

commit_message:
Change default configure "Thick" to "Thin" about LUNType

The default of LUNType is "Thin",but configure huawei-storage-driver.xml
about LUNType " <LUNType>Thick<LUNType>"  ,It should  change "Thick" to "Thin"

Change-Id: I89ced65bf9682e243231907d946255c2a8113bd7
Closes-Bug: #1505145

commit_message:
Sync deployment tasks on fuel-library upgrade

Simple yum update could break redeployments because
a given task could be changed or deleted. Therefore,
an attempt or warning should be made to update
deployment tasks.

Added explicit dependency on fuelclient.

Change-Id: I06a905aa0bbaefbeb7cbdc60b563f11575bd5bd8
Closes-Bug: #1475530

commit_message:
Fix sysinfo resource declaration

This change replaces the use of clone resources as each node may have a
different disk layout. Additionally this change replaces cs_location
with cs_rsc_location which has a proper autorequire for the cs_resource
being defined.

Change-Id: Ifa8a6932c0f0ba2bc05bc0ea9278cbfbe5ae8bb9
Closes-Bug: #1501410

commit_message:
Wait for rabbitmq sync before stop/demote actions

Added new OCF key stop_time (corresponding to start_time)
Added wait_sync function which tries until start_time/2
for queues on stopped/demoted node to reach synced state.

Added optional [-t timeout] to su_rabbit_cmd function to
provide arbitrary timeout

Change-Id: Iae2211b3d477a9603a58d5eacb12e0fba924861a
Closes-Bug: #1464637

commit_message:
Report error if the choosen algorithm executable is not found

This patch allows Freezer to raise an exception if the user chose
an algorithm whose executable not found in the system and
terminate the backup process

Change-Id: I0c9a8a1daa3b44537677ce0f40ebbca52fddc057
Closes-Bug: #1503203

Sorry for not noticing earlier, I get confused somehow.'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2015-10-07 07:25:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Andreas, Doug,

Maybe there is a misunderstanding on the kind of testing we want to achieve.

The networking-bgpvpn project hasn't forked a stable/liberty branch yet and the goal was to test each of our changes against both neutron master and against neutron stable/liberty (seeing a test job fail against neutron master is not an indication for us that our code is broken against liberty, but liberty is the current target that we have - we're release independent and I would not expect to have to fork at the same time as neutron). The intent was to remove the liberty specific job once networking-bgpvpn forks a stable/liberty branch.

If I remove the liberty specific job definition in this change, will the above be achieved (i.e. test each of our change against neutron stable/liberty) ?  (my understanding was 'no', but I don't have a thorough understanding of jenkins/zuul config)

Maybe the above is an unreasonable thing to do, but I would expect some (many?) release-independent networking-* projects to possibly have a similar need to not fork a stable/liberty branch earlier than needed.

Know, a last question: later, networking-bgpvpn will fork a stable/liberty branch to adapt to neutron changes for Mitaka. Can we expect that to happen automatically, or will we have to change the "DEVSTACK_LOCAL_CONFIG='enable_plugin networking-bgpvpn ..." statement in the networking-bgpvpn.yaml job template, to make it point to our stable/liberty branch explicitly ?'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-10-07 07:28:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Thomas, every job will run on every branch unless you specify it otherwise. With branch-override: default, you do not change the branch.'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2015-10-07 07:40:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-10-07 07:46:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-07 07:52:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

There still are some questions on which I do not have a complete understanding:
- you say that "every job will run on every branch", but here we know that networking-bgpvpn code will fail against stable/kilo ; this is fine for an experimental job, but would be a problem for a gate job
- if this job template was triggered on neutron changes in the stable/liberty branch, wouldn't any explicit branch control be needed to retrieve the 'right' branch in networking-bgpvpn (which would be 'master' now, but will be "stable/liberty' once networking-bgpvpn forks such a branch) ?'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-10-07 09:28:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: -Code-Review

Validate domain when adding to SAN extension

Make sure that only valid domains can be added to an extension.

Change-Id: Ia512f4dd20e92dee7d44931a8d790be542a62e24
Closes-bug: 1491080

I think the original intent was as follows, but I'm not sure if it is still entirely true:

The "live" tests runs against "live" services started by devstack in the gate and use information provided by aodh/tests/functional/hooks/post_test_hook.sh

So whereas the other functional tests use a wsgi-intercept api server, the live ones use a real running web server (started by devstack).

commit_message:
Do not try to delete server from deleted Heat stack

Because now Environment's .destroy method would
be called before that of an Instance the later will try
to delete itself from the stack that is physically not
existing and represented as an empty dictionary in
HeatStack.current().

With this change Instance will check stack existence
before deleting anything.

Also a method to check if Instance is present in Heat
stack template was added so that application could check
if it is safe to use the instance (for example to send Agent plans)

Change-Id: I298f3f079a153ef87ed7213b7f1432c9e5e4b4b6
Closes-Bug: #1503715

commit_message:
Revert adding DHCP App by default

Currently not having the DHCP service enabled causes errors
in the plugin and also erros in the App as the DHCP port is not
created.
This patch temporary remove DHCP app from the default installation
until resolved

Change-Id: Ic2759663b8bac1add85edd80ad1b416ff15b277e

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes, the
init.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize all
logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place.

commit_message:
Grab passthrough horizon.allowed_hosts

The tripleo-heat-templates review at
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/221255 adds a HorizonAllowedHosts
parameter. For os-apply-config based deploys make sure this is
set in the horizon image-element etc/horizon/local_settings.py

Depends-On: I5faede8b74a0318e15baa761dc502b95b051ae0d
Change-Id: I0c3de37e4345c5da8b52f6ff664f011376233fe4

commit_message:
aggregates: normalize timestamp

This code is broken with Pandas 0.17 because the timestamps are not all
normalize. This patch fixes that and makes it also compatible with older
Pandas version.

Change-Id: Ie86bb58213a1fc5a25b80b25c330c5f271ebd4ea

commit_message:
Fix TypeError on comparison on Python 3

On Python 3, comparison between None and int or comparison between
dictionaries raises a TypeError.

LaunchForm: use 0 default value instead of None to compare it to 1.

sort() and sorted(): use a key function to compare strings instead of
comparing dictionaries.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I0664c2f6c19c3f105da8b4b5a72cea4eb02c245d

I can delay them, yes. I saw no bigger open review requests for the install guide and thought it is fine to include the changes there right now.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-11 15:01:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkniceness http://logs.openstack.org/51/233451/2/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkniceness/eff387b/ : SUCCESS in 2m 35s

Depending on the service complexity, updates for a release can take several days or more to fully validate, at least for me given other duties. For better or worse, I tend to work locally and make patches mostly complete before uploading them. If I realize a change to a service may impact other parts of the guide, I usually send a note to the e-mail list. If it helps, I could upload a very small patch when I begin working on a particular service, but it probably wouldn't indicate all of the files that a mostly complete or final patch would impact."}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-10-11 16:38:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Also, Git doesn't necessarily handle rebases of documentation structure/syntax very well, especially with a bunch of white space or line length changes. Hence, such changes that impact the installation guide and other release-critical documentation should probably wait until the Liberty testing matrix indicates successful testing for each of the distros we intend to publish."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-10-11 16:40:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for your explanations, Matt. I will remove the files changed in the install guide when I completed an other review. We can cleanup the install guide after completing the liberty spec.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-10-11 17:16:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Christian,

I don't see a need for this cleanup. Based on the discussion both forms are fine and neither will get a -1.

So, this won't get a +2 from me, I consider it just a waste of all our time. I'm not blocking it either, just commenting that  I won't review it..."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-10-11 17:20:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Btw. this will break translations of the manuals and therefore I suggest to not do these cleanups at all.

If you change text for other reasons, go for it - but let's not break already translated content."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-10-11 18:01:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I like to have a consistent syntax in all RST files. It is fine for me to not clean up the syntax if this is the viewpoint of the majority. Should I move this discussion to the mailing list?'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-10-11 18:04:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-10-12 09:55:08.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

we decided to no clean up'}]

commit_message:
Replace 'confirmed' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMED.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMED to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'confirmed'.

Change-Id: I0363042ae3be700a1b8de5b027d6533e8fd53633
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

subject: Replace 'confirming' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMING.

commit_message:
Replace 'confirming' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'confirming'.

Change-Id: I87411bd6f91caf88d8ae7cbe103ba550d37aa177
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Replace 'reverting' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_REVERTING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_REVERTING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'reverting'.

Change-Id: I79c9f43901bc1e9be1b9bc7eae771e04cd9f1778
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Replace 'error' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_ERROR.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_ERROR to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'error'.

Change-Id: I5f349ca0a04a4de8566fb2148e261c7b9e1ac765
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Replace 'reverted' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_REVERTED.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_REVERTED to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'reverted'.

Change-Id: Ie8946f4ee12bed0751c30a26d2fe2ebed56b3c32
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

Additionally,
You might consider using a constants.py instead , so nova/common/constants.py or something similar, since the migration status values might possibly be reused by other components. This is the pattern used by neutron and cinder, while not having a constants.py , does have a config.py in its cinder/common directory.

MIGRATION_STATUS_QUEUED MIGRATION_STATUS_FAILED ...

commit_message:
Replace 'queued' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_QUEUED.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_QUEUED to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'queued'.

Change-Id: I856c33b4e1e4024aba0d5d3d4a6bd13367a556fc
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Replace 'done' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'done'.

'done' status is used only once in the source code, and it is the same
with 'finished'. So reuse MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED.

Change-Id: I3136b9e08d79775d8114e7706b4111d7246ad383
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

subject: Replace 'completed' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED.

commit_message:
Replace 'completed' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'completed'.

'completed' and 'finished' statuses are the same. So reuse
MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED.

Change-Id: I552e4d579d3b6cc1b201e786e90cf3de02550113
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

Hi, thanks for the patches, but seems a bp need to be approved first. And, do we really need to split this into so many patches? it is really hard to review.'}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-09-30 10:57:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi, zheng,

Thanks to reply.

But I don't quite understand why you think it is hard to review. There are 16 different statuses, some of which are used lots of times in the source code. If we put all these in one single patch, it will related to a lot of files, and in each file, several statuses will be changed. It is just too large to me. Is that easy to review to you guys ?

I think split it into one patch for each status is better because it is more clear. For example, it is easier for a reviewer to find out if I missed somewhere needs to be modified. And it is also easier for me to update the patch for a new version. For example, if some one has some comments for one status, I only need to modify one of the patch. I don't need to grep the whole tree to find where I need to update.

Actually, I like smaller patches. One patch for one thing. They are easier to  understand, comment and rebase. Bigger patches are different to make, rebase and debug. If you don't mind, and the CI system won't go crazy, I would like to keep it like this. 

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-10-01 10:50:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-01 12:27:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Replace 'finished' statuses with MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'finished'.

Change-Id: Id9d7112d610ace080d42345759e9930cfeb066a5
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Replace 'post-migrating' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_POST_MIGRATING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_POST_MIGRATING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'post-migrating'.

commit_message:
Replace 'running' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'running'.

'running' status is only used once in the source code. And it has no difference
with 'migrating'. So reuse the MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING.

Change-Id: If1fda9e0ea84b35a9c987aecc55db588d71745a4

commit_message:
Replace 'migrating' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'migrating'.

Change-Id: Ie9e9ac199edcde189e2416d8815e28241d9e35af

commit_message:
Replace 'pre-migrating' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_PRE_MIGRATING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_PRE_MIGRATING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'pre-migrating'.

Change-Id: I19e30256967bb9302ec4329d80bf4dd037e434db
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Replace 'preparing' status with MIGRATION_STATUS_PREPARING.

Use MIGRATION_STATUS_PREPARING to represent the migration status
instead of pure string 'preparing'.

Change-Id: Ic5269e99d5f77a6b30dd539a81e3e7c601fb7eb5
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

(2 comments)

So the -2 is because the blueprint is not yet approved.

I also have some massive issues with this approach. The blueprint review is designed to avoid having to rework so much code after changing direction. Some comments are inline.

I think it would be better to look at how the enum field works here, and do something similar for stats:
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/objects/migration.py#L50
But I am unsure if the objects experts would agree with me.

I don't think its totally worth having a separate commit for each of those status changes, but they are simple enough I guess."}, {'account_id': 15888, 'date': '2015-10-02 14:24:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

mee too, no need to split them into so many patches.'}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-10-05 08:40:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Hi John,

So how could I get the BP approved? And usually, how long will it take to approve a BP? And during this time, what should I do to help? 

During discussion, the direction changes. E.g, string -> translated string -> enum field -> maybe something else -> ...... . Should I change the BP without writing code until the BP is approved?

Sometimes, I saw blueprints with very simple explanation. I really doubt that if people can tell what a direction is from it. 

I think perhaps patches should be submitted at the same time as the BP is published. And the BP will be modified and approved during patch reviewing. 

And so many guys have said that the patches are too many. And OK, I will squash them in the next version.

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-10-05 08:46:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Zheng,

Thank you for reviewing. One question I want to ask, if the number of patches becomes less in the next version, like from 17 to 7, what should I do  with the change ID? Reuse the first 7 ones or create new ones ?

And would you please tell me your advice about for a problem like this, whose total lines of code is about 200+, how many patches are suitable? Or, does openstack community have any rule of splitting patches? We don't really want the code in one single patch, do we?

Sorry, I'm new here. :)

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-10-05 11:26:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)

I replied John's comments in the source code.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-10-08 21:20:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-2

I don't think these status strings need to be codified like this.

Nikola was working on a state field and state machine for migrations, which ensures not only that the states are consistent but that the transitions are understood."}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-10-09 01:18:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Hi Dan,

Would you please share a url of his work, the state machine ?

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 15888, 'date': '2015-10-09 03:28:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Tang Chen, Hi, sorry for reply so late, it's the Nation's Day :-). It really depends on what you are working on, as changes like this, I think it is suitable to do it in a single patch, because it is only refactoring the string, even there are so many lines, but it is easy to understand."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-10-09 08:26:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

The blueprint and spec approval process goes like this, and generally should happen before any code is written, ideally:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Nova/Liberty_Release_Schedule#How_do_I_get_my_code_merged.3F

We have a completing approach already in progress here, so we are likely to not approve this blueprint, we you to work together to find a common solution.'}, {'account_id': 14937, 'date': '2015-10-12 09:35:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Will fix this problem in another way: using a state machine.
Refer to: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/197668/'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-26 11:26:28.000000000', 'message': 'Introduce a MigrationStatus class to indicate live migration status.

In the current code, live migration statuses (Migration.status) are
represented with pure String.

All the task states are defined in task_states.py, and referred by
task_states.XXX. So we can do the same to live migration statuses.

The solution is simple: define all live migration statuses in a new
file, migration_status.py.

There are 16 migration statuses in the current code, and they will be
mapped to the macros below:
1. preparing            : migration_status.PREPARING
2. pre-migrating        : migration_status.PREPARING
3. migrating            : migration_status.MIGRATING
4. running              : migration_status.MIGRATING
5. post-migrating       : migration_status.PREPARING
6. finished             : migration_status.FINISHED
7. completed            : migration_status.FINISHED
8. done                 : migration_status.FINISHED
9. queued               : migration_status.QUEUED
10. confirming          : migration_status.CONFIRMING
11. confirmed           : migration_status.CONFIRMED
12. reverting           : migration_status.REVERTING
13. reverted            : migration_status.REVERTED
14. error               : migration_status.ERROR
15. failed              : migration_status.FAILED
16. dummy               : migration_status.DUMMY

I cannot tell the difference between "migrating"(3) and "running"(4),
and the difference among "finished"(6), "completed"(7), and "done"(8).
So for them, only MIGRATING and FINISHED are defined.

Change-Id: Ie7b12a84e82ebbab3f990a60a7e2fe7dbd3129b6
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Introduce constants to indicate live migration status.

In the current code, live migration statuses (Migration.status) are
represented with pure String. It would be better to define them in
constants because they could also be used by other components.

In Neutron and Cinder, common constants are defined in a directory
named "common". So we can do the same to live migration statuses in
Nova.

The solution is simple: define all live migration statuses in a new
file, nova/common/constants.py.

There are 16 migration statuses in the current code, and they will be
mapped to the constatns as below:
1. preparing            : MIGRATION_STATUS_PREPARING
2. pre-migrating        : MIGRATION_STATUS_PRE_MIGRATING
3. migrating            : MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING
4. running              : MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING
5. post-migrating       : MIGRATION_STATUS_POST_MIGRATING
6. finished             : MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED
7. completed            : MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED
8. done                 : MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED
9. queued               : MIGRATION_STATUS_QUEUED
10. confirming          : MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMING
11. confirmed           : MIGRATION_STATUS_CONFIRMED
12. reverting           : MIGRATION_STATUS_REVERTING
13. reverted            : MIGRATION_STATUS_REVERTED
14. error               : MIGRATION_STATUS_ERROR
15. failed              : MIGRATION_STATUS_FAILED
16. dummy               : MIGRATION_STATUS_DUMMY

I cannot tell the difference between "migrating"(3) and "running"(4),
and the difference among "finished"(6), "completed"(7), and "done"(8).
So for them, only MIGRATION_STATUS_MIGRATING and MIGRATION_STATUS_FINISHED
are defined.

Change-Id: Ie7b12a84e82ebbab3f990a60a7e2fe7dbd3129b6
Implements: blueprint live-migration-statuses

commit_message:
Assert has_calls in tests

Instead of assert_has_calls, tests were wrongly using has_calls.

Corrected the same in this patch.

Also fix bugs in corresponding functions.

Co-Authored-By: Sergey Kraynev <skraynev@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Idcd44a6833bb4a193767112065ce933deb7d1464

commit_message:
Use assertTrue(observed) instead of assertEqual(True, observed)

We should use assertTrue not assertEqual.

Closes-Bug: #1503071

Change-Id: Ib75dd9f8965fd04fe581f09a5e5df3df43542d89

commit_message:
Refactor network availability for node check

Code of NetAssignmentValidator.validate updated with additional check
which determines whether networks in input data can be assigned to node.
The decision is made upon availability of particular net for node group
in which the node is included. The validation is meant to substitute
another check that does the same yet uses already assigned to the node's
nics networks which has produced errorful behavior in some cases (see
the bug's description)

Change-Id: I028b50e32d7bf1b9d02674b861e2e5ff24b4f2d5
Closes-bug: #1425907

commit_message:
Modify value of 'ALLOWED_HOSTS'

"ALLOWED_HOSTS= '*'" should be "ALLOWED_HOSTS= ['*']" in
install-guide.It is should be consistent with
the previous configuration specification.

Change-Id: Ib04a3d80ab1b490cf808e05ca55c6845a0f1893b
Closes-bug: #1505086

Currently iterations results are saved in order of their
completion. For example, we have iterations 1, 2, 3, 4, and
iterations 1 and 3 runs too long, so we could have results
stored in order 2, 4, 1, 3. This causes mistakes in results
analysis.

This patch adds key "iteration" to each iteration result,
and also sorts results with buffering, so we have iterations

Closes-Bug: #1492583
'}]
commit_message:
[Fix] Get iterations results by their start order

Currently iterations results are saved in order of their
completion. For example, we have iterations 1, 2, 3, 4, and
iterations 1 and 3 runs too long, so we could have results
stored in order 2, 4, 1, 3. This causes mistakes in results
analysis.

This patch adds key "iteration" to each iteration result,
and also sorts results with buffering, so we have iterations
in their start order.

Change-Id: I553e8835f766c852d56d86ddca62eebdcff82c04
Closes-Bug: #1492583

commit_message:
Add Neutron LBaaS V1 healthmonitor scenarios

This patch adds the following Neutron Loadbalancer V1
Healthmonitor scenarios
* Create and list healthmonitors
* Create and delete healthmonitors
* Create and update healthmonitors

Change-Id: I5a6bda34446d8ec3e11b8f589bfc17b14f23ce4c

commit_message:
Simplify rpc_backend parameter

It is no longer necessary to specify the whole python namespace
for the backends, and
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.messaging/opts.html lists
the short versions.

This patch maintains backwards compatibility with the previous
default value in case it is explicitly used.

Change-Id: Ie8f298c86266aec249071dc25ce2263c17e65a57

commit_message:
Pass necessary options to Apache when using WSGI

Keystone recommend to use WSGIApplicationGroup and WSGIPassAuthorization
options when is running under Apache. When WSGIApplicationGroup is not set,
import failures are observed and Keystone doesn't work as expected.

Change-Id: I30483d269f6ae6edcecd376d6814c80c0166b265
Closes-bug: #1502318

subject: Pass necessary options to Apache when using WSGI

commit_message:
Pass necessary options to Apache when using WSGI

It's recommended to use WSGIApplicationGroup and WSGIPassAuthorization
options when a service is running under Apache.

Change-Id: Ia6bacab44c1d25f0253c84183f4a561d7682c6e8

useful if nodes are stuck on transition, like deploying.

Change-Id: Ie84b44affb710518e703cc69c217cdd5f64a11f0
"}, {'created': '2015-06-09 08:06:07.000000000', 'message': "Check timeout when nodes stuck on deploying state

Nodes could be stuck on deploying state if the conductor break
and restart. It's necessary to mark nodes as failed when the
transient(deploying) action timeout. As the conductor restart,
it will clear the reservation of nodes on the host, so in this

A case without restart (reservation='fake-reserv') is addressed

"}, {'created': '2015-06-10 03:47:58.000000000', 'message': "Check timeout when nodes stuck on deploying state

Nodes could be stuck on deploying state if the conductor break
and restart. It's necessary to mark nodes as failed when the
transient(deploying) action timeout. As the conductor restart,
it clears reservation for nodes reserved by this conductor, so
in this case 'reservation=NULL'.

The case that nodes are still reserved by the conductor, is
addressed in next patch.

"}]
commit_message:
Check timeout when nodes stuck on deploying state

Nodes could be stuck on deploying state if the conductor break
and restart. It's necessary to mark nodes as failed when the
transient(deploying) action timeout. As the conductor restart,
it clears reservation for nodes reserved by this conductor, so
in this case 'reservation=NULL'.

The case that nodes are still reserved by the conductor, is
addressed in next patch.

Partial Bug: #1461937
Change-Id: Ie84b44affb710518e703cc69c217cdd5f64a11f0

commit_message:
Add support to return request_id of last request

Thread local storage is used for storing openstack request ids.

Added method 'store_x_openstack_request_id' which will store request_id
to thread local storage of client. This method is called after request
is made to glance service.

Added method 'get_x_openstack_request_id' which will return request_id
stored in thread local storage of client.

blueprint: expose-get-x-openstack-request-id
Change-Id: I87a5112b3737fb8e8d39412af5eff7647e89c973

commit_message:
Consume sslutils and wsgi modules from oslo.service

sslutils and basic WSGI functionality have been moved to
oslo.service and now Neutron can reuse them.

Marked ssl options that were renamed in oslo.service as
deprecated.

Added a note about possible implications for out-of-tree plugins
to neutron_api.rst

Bumped oslo.service version to 0.9.0.

Related-Bug: #1482633

Depends-On: I0424a6c261fae447dbc25b3abf00258c860a88f5
Change-Id: Ibfdf07e665fcfcd093a0e31274e1a6116706aec2

Allow enabling debug mode for config management (Puppet)

Also adds an environment file which can be passed to heat stack-create
to enable debugging.

Change-Id: I9758e2ca3de6a0bed6d20c37ea19e48f47220721

(1 comment)

> Is there any reason why the registration is staying in the global post-config?

Yeah, Jan and I discussed and decided it was safer to leave the registration post-deploy as we weren't certain if all the external network connectivity would be in place when the server is built but not yet configured by puppet.

If we can get confirmation from Dan^2 that it's OK we can re-combine them.

The Pre/Post naming is mostly due to the historical introduction of the "PostDeploy" configs in overcloud-without-mergepy - I've justified that in the previous patch, suggestions on better naming welcome, but FWIW this is consistent with the current naming in the tree, which is why I used it.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-25 15:06:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Move RHEL (un)registration to NodeExtraConfig

Currently, we have a problem because the unregistration happens in the
"post deploy" phase, which works fine when the top-level stack is being
deleted, but not when the ResourceGroup of servers is being scaled down,
because then the normal "post deploy" update ordering is respected and
we try to unregister after the corresponding server has been deleted.

So, instead, register/unregister each node inside the unit of scale,
e.g the role template being scaled down, which is possible via the new
NodesExtraConfig interface, which means unregistration will take
place at the right time both on stack delete and on scale-down.

Change-Id: I8f117a49fd128f268659525dd03ad46ba3daa1bc

commit_message:
Ensure httpd is not enabled by puppet on system boot

The httpd daemon will be started and managed by Pacemaker, it should
not be enabled by puppet. Ideally, it shouldn't be started either
but it seems it isn't possible with horizon and apache mod_wsgi [1].

1. https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1247547

Change-Id: I8a1b23c4ea27ac86385314f6cfde8c49d0879969
Co-Authored-By: marios andreou (marios@redhat.com)

commit_message:
Glance image delete output

Previously deleting an already deleted image was throwing the error
of "404 Not Found".With this fix, now the error would be "No image
with a name or ID of '' exists

Change-Id: Ie7b60901619a2336a35890efaa819d34e431a5c8
Closes bug #1333119

commit_message:
Add support for Linux Bonding to os-net-config ifcfg

This change adds support for Linux Bonding to the impl_ifcfg
in os-net-config. This change adds support for configuring Linux
Bonds using the Bonding module rather than Open vSwitch. Most of
the options for Linux Bonds are the same as OVS, with the exception
of bonding_options instead of ovs_options.

Change-Id: If8c6de1554234277843de9fac58536dd5b0a941b

Thank you. ;)'}, {'account_id': 3009, 'date': '2015-10-12 07:32:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@zhangguoqing, Centos target image is the image that we use when provisioning Fuel slave nodes (those nodes where we deploy Openstack). At the moment, this centos target image is a part of ISO and this patch is to stop including this image into ISO. We want it to be possible to build this image on the Fuel master node. But in Fuel 7.0 there is no option that allows user to deploy Centos based openstack cluster and I don't know if this option will be available in Fuel 8.0. But if it is available, target image will be built on the master node (the same as for ubuntu)."}, {'account_id': 3009, 'date': '2015-10-12 07:32:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-12 07:32:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
Remove centos target image building

We don't need Centos target images in 8.0, so
this patch comments all the lines related to this.

commit_message:
Add pypi publishing jobs for neutron sub-projects

Make these consistent so we can ensure we're able to publish
releases to pypi. This includes adding pypi-jobs as well as
openstack-publish-jobs.

Note: This excludes the networking-powervm project which has
still not created a PyPi repo yet.

Change-Id: I02ec5166acc91a64ca5e29752c268234e7fbf7cb
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Added MAINTAINERS to top-level repo directory

In a consensus reached in a proposal for code review process
change [1], and proposed team structure policy document [2],
adding MAINTAINERS files in repositories.

Please note, that this file is written in YAML format in order
to allow further automation around code review process.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072406.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225376/1

Change-Id: I54c2ad8f36e88570ad545968933474fc207acc75

commit_message:
Add _needs_update() to AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation

This will enable update-preview to see if the resource will be replaced
during a particular stack-update.

Also, a bit of redundant code was deleted.

Change-Id: Ib368d2edddac6b968e16db9f8e7128ac30ff764f
Partial-Bug: #1494436

commit_message:
Add how to use in Ironic Section

Since Ironic is an integration project now. We should add one section
about it in Admin guide.
This commit is part of the bugfix since adding the whole section is
huge. This one is to add the sequence of how to use Ironic.

Change-Id: I35176fcec960110bfe62c68251a1dfd5d0d828cf
Partial-Bug: #1495898

commit_message:
Use request helpers for token_info/token_auth

There is already a request setter for token_auth that we aren't using
and should be. Also add a setter for token_info rather than set the
environment directly.

This makes it much easier to consume these values later in objects that
subclass BaseAuthProtocol.

Change-Id: I7f4bf2950f783e4dc85a5671def6a02322cd7f8a

commit_message:
Add support for image metadata namespace (Juno)

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/glance/glancemetadefcatalogapi.html
Adding API support for glance namespace create delete and list

- Added md_namespace_create , md_namespace_delete and
  md_namespace_list
- Added test for create_metadefs_namespace and delete
- Added test for list_metadefs_namespaces

I am planning to commit more API commands for namespace support.

Depends-On: I87a5b560285d4520faa3c58968343f15abfc480f
Change-Id: I62710c7c0a2dde34f16845186eb92f915e925119

commit_message:
Have the executor stats object repr look like the watcher repr

Avoid having different repr styles and just unify the executor
stats one to look like the one used in the watcher object, which
is the style more commonly used in other libraries also.

Change-Id: Ibd98094371f57ecb8bca78b8446ca28727da84e9

commit_message:
Fix the bug of "Error spelling of a word"

The word "authentification" should be spelled as "authentication".
So it is changed.

Change-Id: I82cc81561c1b0c615d271a5a75c9d3d8906dff14
Closes-Bug: #1505046

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to

    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Fix redis cluster unit test for assertRaisesRegexp

The redis cluster unit test was updated to use
assertRaisesRegexp rather than assertRaises
to ensure that the correct messages are being generated.

Closes-Bug: #1491918
Change-Id: I89f0da62df7933786424ce2e96815765a66625aa

versioning.

commit_message:
Add more filters for chassis node-list

Add support for filtering chassis nodes by associated, maintenance,
and provision state in the chassis-node-list command.

Closes-Bug: #1416313

commit_message:
Fix tests giving erroneous output during os-testr run

After the switch to os-testr more output is given in console during
the tests run. Some output is stderr due to mistakes in
mocking/logging. This change fixes such tests.

Change-Id: I074c0f3aeb08df04ca9efcf34a7a49415567f466
Closes-bug: #1504524

commit_message:
Fix agent_ilo to remove temporary images

agent_ilo driver doesn't cleanup the temporary
files created. This commit makes sure
that the temporary files are cleaned up before
the server goes for second boot.

Closes-bug: #1503795

Change-Id: I6cce1d1f3a5631e1af992c173379927fed3c55a1

commit_message:
Add unspecified options to backup unittests

The backup runner unittests have been intermittently failing
because some of the backup commands being returned don't include
gzip in the pipeline.

The problem is that the tests all use the same instance of the
BackupRunner and the is_zipped instance variable is being
altered by the various tests. Each test that is expecting
compression and/or encryption needs to set these variables
explicitly. If not, depending on the timing and ordering of
the tests, the variables may not be set as the test expects.

Put defaults for the variables (true) into the setup() method.
Removed code in the tests that set is_zipped or is_encrypted
to true and will rely on the defaults in setup() for these.

Change-Id: I74431aefe88e1aea15ca5160a6cb597b59d19fbd
Closes-bug: 1500199

commit_message:
Allow RBD host to be configurable

Most sites using ceph with cinder are going to have already set the host
value.  This change allows those sites to override the default and not
break existing volumes.  It also moves the tests cases from the volume
class to the backend define.  Lastly, it renames the parameter from host
to backend_host, since host is deprecated with Kilo.

Change-Id: I43e4d3b7ae1672ea0c551c6c7267f0c38bb9842f

commit_message:
Fixing -n behaviour

The old default of -1 to mean "all lines of context" was
none-sensical and has been removed, all lines of context
would be the entire file.

A new default of 3 is used now, to give a line before and
a line after the issue. This is correctly adjustable by the
-n command line option.

Change-Id: I0299e2ff260ae67936342feacb1a30d51bfd55a8
closes-bug: 1497771

commit_message:
Add v2 to method id for separating LBaaS v1/v2 method URL

  separate Method URL for v1/v2
  by adding v2 in method.

for v1
http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-networking-v2-ext.html#createPool
  for v2 (changed)
  http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-networking-v2-ext.html#createPoolv2

Closes-Bug: #1504511
Change-Id: I4e347be2de662718be18465d0843dcf78ae09407

commit_message:
VPNaaS: Multiple Local Subnet API documentation

Documents changes for the multiple local subnet support on IPSec
site-to-site connections. This new capability uses the endpoint
groups API, on which this commit is based.

Changes include:

- The subnet ID is now optional (and deprecated) for the VPN service API.
- The peer CIDR attribute is deprecated and replaced by local and peer
  endpoint group IDs (former for subnets, and latter for CIDRs) for
  the site-to-site connection API.
- Commit I0cdded5105ad8000131e39a86cbfa80ed89ae37b added external IP
  address reporting for the VPN service, and that includes IPv4 and
  IPv6 addresses in the show VPN service output. Along with updated
  examples, the fields were added and sample information was updated
  for this feature.

Related-Bug: #1459423
Closes-Bug: #1504881

Change-Id: Ib19a50b069b74b30f81f515390151925e7fd6366

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in some test file of zaqarclient.
The review is generated part-wise to ease review process.
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: I3f51e3a400d1c408e6c65b9ed503efd414b3d5ed

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

This patch fix the issue in the module /tests/queues/ of zaqarclient.
The review is generated part-wise to ease review process.
Partial-Bug: #1259292

Change-Id: I405ca85d497361b41ada5eab567dd9735e787c32

commit_message:
Save updated-in-place resources to backup stack

The patch changes the approach of resource backup during stack
update. It stores the definition of resource that needs to be
updated in-place to backup stack(if it was not created before).

Without this functionality, InvalidTemplateReference will be thrown
every time when update-replaced resource has a reference to updated
in-place resource and stack update was failed. In this case, backup
stack has a resource that refers to not-presented another resource
and backup stack deletion generates an exception.

Change-Id: I436c44a579bb4df3031d1a17b9ca5b62da37afeb
Closes-bug: #1446575
(cherry picked from commits da3777342a344a2dafb9244b7afca8722a398caa
                        and 3786262aed62d81ad35de3d4f703c38223907ffd)

commit_message:
Prevent iRMC unit test from potential failure at the gate

This patch adds the missing mock patcher.stop() which corresponds to
patcher.start() so as not to be a cause of failure at the gate.

Change-Id: I6d3cb6f70550d9f36e33b4b9b5f493784dc0f5dc
Related-Bug: #1503603

commit_message:
Put all the logging related parameters to the logging class

Currently logging configuration is splitted in two distinct classes,
the init.pp and the logging.pp classes. This review aims to centralize
all logging related parameters in a single class, the logging.pp one.

The impacted parameters are :

  * use_syslog
  * use_stderr
  * log_facility
  * verbose
  * debug
  * log_dir

This change remains backward compatible with what is currently in place.

Change-Id: I654f77d9c18401537f738d054d8e6be529d25fa2

'}, {'created': '2015-10-08 21:48:42.000000000', 'message': "Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Ie8f0709bf360d9c4af2559b3278f26cd2cb191f5
"}, {'created': '2015-10-09 17:25:32.000000000', 'message': "Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Ie8f0709bf360d9c4af2559b3278f26cd2cb191f5
Depends-On: I228683aea1a8def46eaac63704e41617ba892438"}]
commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: Ie8f0709bf360d9c4af2559b3278f26cd2cb191f5
Depends-On: I228683aea1a8def46eaac63704e41617ba892438

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Change-Id: I7763fcb25efbe7ccee16f3cf1d796fcfbe977280

commit_message:
rabbitmq: do not manage rabbitmq service anymore

rabbitmq_class was deprecated in the previous release, this patch drop it.

That means:

  * we are not installing rabbitmq service anymore.
  * rabbitmq_class parameter is deleted
  * port, cluster_disk_nodes and enabled parameters are deprecated for
    backward compatibility but port and cluster_disk_nodes have no effect
    since we don't install rabbitmq anymore.
  * unit tests are updated

Change-Id: I01b1dcaeef55c2a5c07f7c2c4b0ad7433eceee7b
Co-Authored-By: Emilien Macchi <emilien@redhat.com>

[{'created': '2015-10-09 15:46:47.000000000', 'message': "metadata: don't crash proxy on non-unicode user data

as per oslo.log docs [1], we should make sure that what we pass into the

bytes in Python 2.x [2].

That's why we need to convert the response content to unicode before
passing it into oslo.log.

still don't crash.

occurs before oslo.log machinery decides it should not log the message.

[1]: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.log/usage.html#no-more-implicit-conversion-to-unicode-str
[2]: http://bitworking.org/projects/httplib2/doc/html/libhttplib2.html#httplib2.Http.request

commit_message:
metadata: don't crash proxy on non-unicode user data

We attempt to log every successful metadata response with LOG.debug. But
as per oslo.log docs [1], we should make sure that what we pass into the
library is unicode.

Http.request returns a tuple of Response object and a string, which is
bytes in Python 2.x [2].

That's why we need to convert the response content to unicode before
passing it into oslo.log.

To achieve it, we utilize encodeutils.safe_decode with 'replace' errors
handling strategy, so that we don't get exceptions on input that does
not conform unicode.

For the unit test case, we pass a string that is not expected to convert
to unicode with errors='strict' strategy or similar, and check that we
still don't crash.

While at it, we remove a check for the number of log calls being
triggered, because it's something that we should avoid validating in
test cases, and it cannot trigger a real bug. The mock that was used to
count the number would also hide the bug that we try to reproduce.

Note that the bug does not require debug to be set because the crash
occurs before oslo.log machinery decides it should not log the message.

[1]: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.log/usage.html#no-more-implicit-conversion-to-unicode-str
[2]: http://bitworking.org/projects/httplib2/doc/html/libhttplib2.html#httplib2.Http.request

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/metadata/namespace_proxy.py
	neutron/tests/unit/agent/metadata/test_namespace_proxy.py

Closes-Bug: #1501772
Change-Id: I6a32c40ff117fae43913386134c8981539697ce8
(cherry picked from commit 80e3d9be4923ecad17377b1d15c8392b8a43dac6)

commit_message:
usage_audit: Fix usage_audit to work with ML2

The script didn't work with the ML2 plugin as router related
functionality is moved to the L3 router service plugin. The fix assumes
that the L3 router service plugin is in use, and this seems to apply to
most of the current core plugins.

Change-Id: If3eb7bde4a5b8b9ca2ac0bd7327325f6c0ad620a
Closes-Bug: 1481692
(cherry picked from commit 2bded62d6a6a141e610a06e5f40bb28c0b26da5c)

Add "ipsec_site_connection" into Req/res params table

Following APIs are missing "ipsec_site_connection" at Req/res param table:

* Show ipsec_site_connection
  * Add "ipsec_site_connection" into response params table
* Create ipsec_site_connection
  * Add "ipsec_site_connection" into Req/res params table
* Update ipsec_site_connection
  * Add "ipsec_site_connection" into Req/res params table

Closes-Bug: #1504543

commit_message:
Add "network(s)" into Req/res params table

Following APIs are missing "network(s)" at Req/res param table:

  * List networks
    * Add "networks" into response params table
  * Show network
    * Add "network" into response params table
  * Create network
    * Add "network" into Req/res params table
  * Update network
    * Add "network" into Req/res params table

Change-Id: I06ba7e57e3a049000d4e53735296fc6d23de8ddf
Partial-bug: #1504427

commit_message:
Enable ARP responder for L2 population

Local ARP responder is needed to serve ARP broadcasts locally on compute node
by neutron OVS agent. This is a part of L2 population feature.

Closes-bug: #1483584
Change-Id: Ic1f1809fa93fa8fc715ff638a9e365b49a0e1af4

commit_message:
Collapse Compute API v2 and v2.1 together

Collapse into a single Compute API docs because
there is only one Compute API.

This combination should help with both maintenance and future
migration work.

Partial-Bug: #1491227

Change-Id: I84c0b011c6c1c4cf7bff7793591eb41a847b7618

commit_message:
VPNaaS Endpoint Group API

Documents the new endpoint group API, which defines
"what gets connected" for VPN connections. This is intended to
support the multiple local subnet feature for IPSec site-to-site
connections, but is usable for other flavors of VPN.

Change-Id: I6a053c81613adf344cc55211f7cbdc915a7c75c3
Related-Bug: #1459423
Closes-Bug: #1504880

commit_message:
Add create/delete for keystone roles

This completes the replacement of: Ifd74cbcef9dd0f3531912995da8ad7b75dd19d44

Add create and delete methods for roles. Note that there is no
update method (the review we are replacing had an update method).
This is because keystone v2 does NOT have support for this, only
v3.

Change-Id: Ib037484c38673f10bd2b2fe2df5ca87056d06e6d

commit_message:
Add option to floating ip creation to not reuse

Although reusing available floating ips is potentially a more
efficient use of resources in the cloud, it's a more expensive
amount of API calls. Additionally, if the user knows that they
are deleting floating ips with servers, then attempting to
reuse is just going to be a waste of effort.

Co-Authored-By: James E. Blair <jeblair@linux.vnet.ibm.com>
Change-Id: Ibfb7583232b03bcf29df229862f6da97170aa845

commit_message:
Add methods to update internal router interfaces

Adding internal interfaces to a router is a useful thing. This adds
methods that will allow a user to add and remove them as separate steps.
A possible next step will be to allow this to be done during router
creation.

Change-Id: Ieb007de3d68d5b8a972df5178c032add8e59377a

commit_message:
Add get/list/search methods for identity roles

This partially replaces: Ifd74cbcef9dd0f3531912995da8ad7b75dd19d44

Adds read methods for identity roles. Note that the original
code (referenced above) puts these methods in OpenStackCloud, but
this puts these methods in OperatorCloud because these methods
require admin-level privileges in keystone's policy file.

Change-Id: I896972eb08a804b5dc6cd9c87a754598a90933a5
Co-Authored-By: Haneef Ali <haneef.ali@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>

[{'created': '2015-10-09 18:15:20.000000000', 'message': "Do not log an error when deleting a linuxbridge does not exist

When you're racing to teardown and relying on RPC, it should not be
considered an error that a bridge does not exist when you're trying to
delete it anyway. This is better served as debug level information.

For context, this shows up over 1000 times in successful
gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-linuxbridge job runs in a week so it's
probably safe to say it's not contributing to test failures.

Closes-Bug: #1501779

Change-Id: I8e9b27e010d033291497f4e660a97bbae92e75b1
(cherry picked from commit a9dc48f5a4616a505824c3e8520c3dce7436f1b1)
"}]
commit_message:
Do not log an error when deleting a linuxbridge does not exist

When you're racing to teardown and relying on RPC, it should not be
considered an error that a bridge does not exist when you're trying to
delete it anyway. This is better served as debug level information.

For context, this shows up over 1000 times in successful
gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-linuxbridge job runs in a week so it's
probably safe to say it's not contributing to test failures.

Closes-Bug: #1501779

Change-Id: I8e9b27e010d033291497f4e660a97bbae92e75b1
(cherry picked from commit a9dc48f5a4616a505824c3e8520c3dce7436f1b1)

Some comments inline. The main issue I have is the chosen path appears to be a stateless firewall, which cannot replicate all of the behavior of a stateful firewall. Because of this, this cannot be automatically upgraded to or chosen as the default without warnings to the deployers.

Perhaps there needs to be a flag in the security groups that show whether the underlying implementation is stateful or stateless so users understand how they will have to setup rules.'}, {'account_id': 6670, 'date': '2014-05-16 15:15:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

We have a couple obstacles: API implementation parity and ML2 driver extensions. 

1. Having behavioral parity with security groups API implementation is important to Neutron users, but is impossible with current capabilities with OVS.

2. An API extension supported by a single backend MechanismDriver in ML2 (e.g. openvswitch in this case) does not apply to all backend drivers.'}, {'account_id': 2031, 'date': '2014-05-22 00:30:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Amir: I am now concerned about a few things with this patch, can you clarify these for me?

1. What is the flow explosion like for this new feature per VM and per security group rule?
2. This no longer provides equivalent functionality as iptables firewalls due to the lack of OVS features. We can document this, but this will be confusing for users.
3. If connection tracking is implemented in OVS, per this discussion here [1], do we even need this feature?
4. I have a patch to reprogram flows on OVSDB/OVS restart [2]. Does this affect your work here?

[1] http://openvswitch.org/pipermail/dev/2014-May/040567.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/95060/'}, {'account_id': 6670, 'date': '2014-05-23 19:53:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

1. In the general case, it should be a fixed amount per VM and then linearly per security group rule added. Certain edge cases, like a port-range wider than one port, will lead to multiple flows per rule.


2. I agree. Any ideas on how to mitigate the confusion other than documentation and runtime warnings? 


3. Connection tracking will not be available in an OVS release until 2015. I'd argue 80% of the utility of security groups is captured in the blueprint today. Do we, as a community, want an 80% solution today or wait one year for a 100% solution?


4. No, I was concerned with the agent restarting more than OVS components restarting. Hence, blueprint neutron-agent-soft-restart."}, {'account_id': 6670, 'date': '2014-05-28 20:33:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-28 20:33:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Looking at the current state of agents, I motion to table this blueprint until significant refactoring occurs, specifically the Modular L2 Agent blueprint @banix has authored thus far[1]. I'd like to see an improved, re-usable agent architecture before any additional features are added to the agent. I won't be able to be able to attend this upcoming design summit, but I'll try to follow along remotely.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/106189/"}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-11-08 22:27:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I think that the request to table the blueprint is proper.  I'd suggest that you abandon the blueprint for now.  When we're ready to revive this effort the spec review can be reactivated."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-11-10 15:54:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I would also like to have a level of proof that flow based sgs perform better than iptables ones which goes beyon "iptables is crap" or "yeah, the guy over there say it's faster" (when the guy over there is actually selling hot dogs)'}, {'account_id': 6670, 'date': '2014-11-10 16:12:09.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Marking as abandoned per Mark McClain.'}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2015-08-31 12:14:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

One argument in favor of this patch: 

Since OVS is now supported on Windows, we currently don't have a unified firewall driver (IPTables is Linux specific).

It would be great to handle security groups in a unified way as well and this patch provides what is needed.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 11604, 'date': '2015-08-31 13:29:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I agree it would be nice to have a single ovs based implementation that worked with the dpdk,linux kernel and windows datapaths.

A learn action based implementation based off of the connection tracking implementation is currently under review here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/216627/

the implementation above can work with both the dpdk and linux kernel datapath if ovs is  built form the maste(the 2.4 release may also have the required openflow supprot/nicira extensions but did not test this). it may work with the windows datapath but that was never tested.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-08-31 15:18:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

The only thing we are waiting for upstream is connection tracking support in OVS.

I'm curious, how will that work in Windows without the presence of conntrack?"}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2015-09-11 19:54:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Kevin a conntrack OVS Windows compatible implementation is currently being discussed'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-09-11 20:27:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

OVS connection tracking is now upstream in the kernel and will be a part of OVS 2.5 if I'm not mistaken."}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2015-09-11 21:39:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@kyle, correct. I was referring to the Windows support.'}]

commit_message:
Adds some lines to complete table formatting

Currently the vendor support list is mis-formatted for the last
two entries on the page. It appears that the tables don't have
lines underneath them completing the formatting.

This patch adds lines under the last two vendor entries fixing
the formatting of the tables for those entries.

Change-Id: I6327eef99059291fcce5c9493a622bec33da3824

Add PROVIDER variable

Add a PROVIDER variable. Currently, the default and only valid value
is virtualbox. In the near future, kvm should become another valid
value.

commit_message:
Add code to determine ssh port from node name

Add a new function, ssh_env_for_node: it takes a node name and returns
the correct ssh port (port forwarding from configuration files) as soon
as the sshd gives a response.

Change-Id: Ic3b7cebdd2d52befe7e02897d09da83c34373beb

commit_message:
Refactor use of basedisk name/path

The basedisk name (and hence get_base_disk_name) have the filename
extension .vdi removed to allow for backends that have different
file extensions.

The VirtualBox-specific function get_base_disk_path is moved from
functions-host.sh to virtualbox-functions.sh.

Change-Id: I27c0b2d50717da60df6fd743d49e64d3a066c9cd

commit_message:
Rename boot functions from vbox_ to vm_

Code to boot VMs is VirtualBox-specific, but other hypervisors will
differ in implementation, not function name. This patch makes the
function name generic.

Change-Id: I31f52e89164582415dce6b09cecdc39bc8031b8a

commit_message:
Log file handling in repeat-test.sh

Write the test log into LOG_DIR during execution and move it to the
archive only after the test has run its course.

After the test, don't abort if not all log files exist.

Change-Id: I31ffce757e53e0e1b288a71bc06ff191760775cd
